 Vendetta''\n| rowspan=\"3\"| Warner Bros.\n| March 17, 2006\n| 73% (248 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= V for Vendetta (2006) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/v_for_vendetta |website= Rotten Tomatoes }}</ref>\n| 62 (39 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title=V for Vendetta |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/v-for-vendetta |website=[[Metacritic]]}}</ref>\n| B+<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $54\n| $132,511,035\n|-\n| ''The Losers''\n| April 23, 2010\n| 48% (164 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= The Losers (2010) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/1226860_losers |website= Rotten Tomatoes }}</ref>\n| 44 (32 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= The Losers |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-losers |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref>\n| B<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $25\n| $29,379,723\n|-\n| ''The Kitchen''\n| August 9, 2019\n| 23% (219 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= The Kitchen (2019) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_kitchen |website= Rotten Tomatoes }}</ref>\n| 35 (42 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= The Kitchen |url= https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-kitchen-2019 |website= [[Metacritic]] }}</ref>\n| B\u2013<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $37\n| $15,880,032\n|}\n;Paradox Press\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"\n! Title\n! Distributor(s)\n! Release date\n! Rotten Tomatoes\n! Metacritic\n! CinemaScore<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n! Budget <br />(million)\n! Box Office\n|-\n| ''Road to Perdition''\n| DreamWorks\n| July 12, 2002\n| 80% (215 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title= Road to Perdition (2002) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/road_to_perdition |website= Rotten Tomatoes }}</ref>\n| 72\n| B+<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $80\n| $181,001,478\n|-\n| ''A History of Violence''\n| New Line Cinema\n| May 16, 2005\n| 87% (214 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title=A History of Violence (2005) |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/history_of_violence |website= Rotten Tomatoes }}</ref>\n| 81\n| C+<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $32\n| $60,740,827\n|}\n;WildStorm\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" width=99% border=\"1\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|- style=\"background:#b0c4de;\"\n! Title\n! Distributor(s)\n! Release date\n! Rotten Tomatoes\n! Metacritic\n! CinemaScore<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n! Budget <br />(million)\n! Box Office\n|-\n| ''Gen\u00b9\u00b3''\n| Paramount Pictures\n| October 31, 2000\n| {{NA}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/gen_13 |title=Gen\u00b9\u00b3 (2000) |website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|accessdate=November 7, 2019}}</ref>\n| {{NA}}\n| {{NA}}\n| $6\n| Unknown\n|-\n| ''RED''\n| rowspan=\"2\"| Summit Entertainment\n| October 15, 2010\n| 71% (207 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title=Red (2010) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url= https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/red/ }}</ref>\n| 60\n| A\u2013<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $58\n| $199,006,387\n|-\n| ''RED 2''\n| July 19, 2013\n| 44% (149 reviews)<ref>{{cite web |title=Red 2 (2013) |website= [[Rotten Tomatoes]] |url= https://rottentomatoes.com/m/red_2/ }}</ref>\n| 47\n| B+<ref name=\"DCcs\" />\n| $84\n| $148,075,565\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of television series based on DC Comics publications]]\n* [[List of video games based on DC Comics]]\n* [[Batman in film]]\n* [[Superman in film]]\n* [[DC Extended Universe]]\n* [[List of unproduced DC Comics projects]]\n** [[List of unproduced films based on DC Comics imprints]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://comicscreen.free.fr ComicScreen: Les super h\u00e9ros cr\u00e8vent l'\u00e9cran]\n* [https://watch4hd.com/movie/articles/best-top-superheroes/ Best Superheroes of All Time]\n\n{{DC Comics films}}\n{{DC Comics animated films}}\n{{DC Animated Universe}}\n{{DC Comics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List Of films based on DC Comics}}\n[[Category:Films based on DC Comics| ]]\n[[Category:Lists of films based on comics|DC Comics]]\n[[Category:Superhero films|DC Comics]]\n[[Category:DC Comics-related lists]]\n[[Category:Sequential lists of films based on comics, arranged in chronological order|DC Comics]]\n", "name_user": "OscarFercho", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAnimated films", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_films_based_on_DC_Comics_publications"}
{"title_page": "2020 Taal Volcano eruption", "text_new": "{{short description|Volcanic eruption in the Philippines}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox eruption\n| name = 2020 Taal Volcano eruptionnn\n| image = Taal Volcano - 12 January 2020.jpg\n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = Taal Volcano's January 12, 2020 explosion\n| start_date = January 12, 2020\n| start_time = \n| end_date = January 19, 2020 <br /> (decreased volcanic activity still ongoing)\n| volcano = [[Taal Volcano]]\n| type = Mainly Phreatomagmatic\n| location = [[Batangas]], [[Calabarzon]], Philippines\n| VEI = <!--wait for USGS / PHIVOLCS assessment-->\n| coordinates = {{coord|14|00|38|N|120|59|52|E|display=inline}}\n| map = Taal Volcano Danger Zone.svg\n| map_size = \n| map_caption = Map of Batangas highlighting the areas under the 14-kilometer radius danger zone\n| impact = 39 dead (only 1 direct, 38 indirect) <ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/39-deaths-recorded-during-taal-volcanos-eruption/|title=39 deaths recorded during Taal Volcano\u2019s eruption |publisher=Manila Bulletin|first=Aaron|last=Recuenco|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\nThe eruption of [[Taal Volcano]] in [[Batangas]], [[Philippines]] on January 12, 2020, was a [[phreatic eruption]] from its main crater that spewed ashes across [[Calabarzon]], [[Metro Manila]], and some parts of [[Central Luzon]] and [[Ilocos Region]], resulting to the suspension of classes, work schedules, and flights in the area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211934/list-class-suspensions-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption|title=LIST: Class suspensions due to Taal Volcano eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114132427/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211934/list-class-suspensions-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|title=Taal eruption puts NAIA flights on hold|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]] (PHIVOLCS) subsequently issued an Alert Level 4, indicating \"that a hazardous [[explosive eruption]] is possible within hours to days.\"<ref name=\"Manila Bulletin\">{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/12/alert-level-3-raised-as-taal-volcano-manifests-steam-driven-explosion/|title=Alert Level 3 raised as Taal volcano manifests steam-driven explosion|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112084337/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/12/alert-level-3-raised-as-taal-volcano-manifests-steam-driven-explosion/|archive-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|title=PHIVOLCS warns of 'hazardous explosive eruption' of Taal Volcano soon|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023853/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy January 26, 2020, PHIVOLCS observed an inconsistent, but decreasing volcanic activity in Taal, prompting the agency to downgrade its warning to Alert Level 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/scitech/science/723567/phivolcs-lowers-taal-volcano-alert-level-to-alert-level-3/story/?amp|title=PHIVOLCS lowers Taal Volcano's status to Alert Level 2|publisher=GMA News|first=Erwin|last=Colcol|date=January 26, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> It was until February 14, 2020, when PHIVOLCS finally decided to downgrade the volcano's warning to Alert Level 2, due to consistent decreased volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/725980/phivolcs-lowers-taal-volcano-s-status-to-alert-level-2/story/|title=PHIVOLCS lowers Taal Volcano's status to Alert Level 2|publisher=GMA News|first=Dona|last=Magsino|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/14/Taal-Volcano-alert-level-2.html|title=Taal Volcano status lowered to Alert Level 2|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Volcanic activity ==\n{{update section|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Eruption ===\n[[File:Taal volcano 2020 eruption captured using IP camera.gif|upright=1.27|thumb|right|Phreatic explosion captured at the main crater of Taal Volcano. Video taken from the installed [[IP camera]] of PHIVOLCS monitoring Taal Volcano]]\n\nThe volcano erupted on the afternoon of January 12, 2020, 43 years after its [[Taal Volcano#1965 to 1977 eruption|previous eruption in 1977]].<ref name=\"Manila Bulletin\"/> According to PHIVOLCS director Dr. Renato Solidum,  seismic swarms began at 11 am and were later followed by [[phreatic eruption]] from Volcano Island Main Crater at around 1{{nbsp}}pm [[Philippine Standard Time]] ([[UTC+8]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211871/taal-volcano-erupts|title=BREAKING: Taal volcano spews ash in phreatic eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113142821/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211871/taal-volcano-erupts|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Loud rumbling sounds were also felt and heard from the volcano island. By 2:30{{nbsp}}pm, PHIVOLCS raised the alert status to Alert Level 2, although PHIVOLCS through its Taal Volcano Observatory had advised residents of Volcano Island to evacuate at around 1 pm. {{nbsp}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/12/1984179/phivolcs-hoists-alert-level-2-over-taal-volcano-after-eruption|title=Phivolcs raises alert level to 3 as Taal Volcano spews kilometer-high plumes|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=PhilStar|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113125554/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/12/1984179/phivolcs-hoists-alert-level-2-over-taal-volcano-after-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stronger explosions began by around 3{{nbsp}}pm that spewed an ash column exceeding a kilometer high, prompting PHIVOLCS to upgrade the alert status to Alert Level 3 by 4{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/249103-taal-volcano-phreatic-explosion-january-12-2020|title=Taal Volcano spews ash column 100 meters high|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Rappler]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113034450/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249103-taal-volcano-phreatic-explosion-january-12-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721885/pyroclastic-density-currents-volcanic-tsunami-likely-around-taal-phivolcs/story/|title=Pyroclastic density currents, volcanic tsunami likely around Taal \u2013PHIVOLCS|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721885/pyroclastic-density-currents-volcanic-tsunami-likely-around-taal-phivolcs/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, Solidum confirmed that there was a [[Intrusive rock|magmatic intrusion]] that is likely the cause of the volcano's phreatic eruptions on Sunday morning and afternoon. PHIVOLCS advised evacuation of the towns of [[Balete, Batangas|Balete]], [[San Nicolas, Batangas|San Nicolas]], and [[Talisay, Batangas|Talisay]] in [[Batangas]] and other towns within the shores of [[Taal Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/12/20/taal-volcano-erupts-as-phivolcs-raises-alert-level-2|title=Residents flee Taal island, as volcano spouts giant ash column|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114030350/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/12/20/taal-volcano-erupts-as-phivolcs-raises-alert-level-2|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|title=Evacuations underway as PHIVOLCS raises Alert Level 3 over Taal Volcano|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023853/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 7:30{{nbsp}}pm, PHIVOLCS upgraded the alert status to Alert Level 4 after volcanic activities intensified as \"continuous eruption generated a tall {{convert|10|to|15|km|mi}} steam-laden [[tephra]] column with frequent [[volcanic lightning]] that rained wet [[Ash fall|ashfall]] on the general north as far as [[Quezon City]] and [[Caloocan]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211988/taal-volcano-now-on-alert-level-4|title=Taal Volcano now on Alert Level 4|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113151715/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211988/taal-volcano-now-on-alert-level-4|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Ashfall from the volcano were also experienced in [[Cavite]] and [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], and reached as far as Metro Manila and [[Pampanga]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211958/look-heavy-ashfall-in-batangas-cavite-laguna-after-taal-eruption|title=LOOK: Heavy ashfall in Batangas, Cavite, Laguna after Taal eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113125343/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211958/look-heavy-ashfall-in-batangas-cavite-laguna-after-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721903/ash-fall-from-taal-volcano-reaches-parts-of-metro-manila-ndrrmc/story/|title=Ash fall from Taal Volcano reaches parts of Metro Manila \u2014NDRRMC|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023832/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721903/ash-fall-from-taal-volcano-reaches-parts-of-metro-manila-ndrrmc/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/12/tens-of-thousands-evacuated-as-taal-volcano-violently-erupts-in-the-philippines/|title=Thousands evacuated as Taal Volcano violently erupts in the Philippines|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=New York Post|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205330/https://nypost.com/2020/01/12/tens-of-thousands-evacuated-as-taal-volcano-violently-erupts-in-the-philippines/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phreatic_eruption_of_Taal_Volcano,_12_January_2020_(reduced).gif|thumb|right|Explosion seen from the Tagaytay City viewdeck]]\n\nOn January 13, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that activity in the Main Crater had transitioned into lava fountaining between 2:48{{nbsp}}am to 4:28{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dwiz882am.com/index.php/bulkang-taal-nagbuga-ng-lava-fountain/|title=BULKANG TAAL NAGBUGA NG LAVA FOUNTAIN|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=[[DWIZ]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112221054/https://www.dwiz882am.com/index.php/bulkang-taal-nagbuga-ng-lava-fountain/|archive-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Lava#Lava fountain|lava fountain]] was recorded at 3:20{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212149/lava-fountain-from-taal-volcano|title=LOOK: Lava fountain from Taal Volcano|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205325/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212149/lava-fountain-from-taal-volcano|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]] presented a study that the [[air quality index]] of cities in Metro Manila had worsened; [[Mandaluyong]] had the highest amount of inhalable [[PM10|coarse particulate matter]] (PM<sub>10</sub>) with 118, followed by [[Las Pi\u00f1as]] (108) and [[Taguig]] (104), all of which were \"considered unhealthy for sensitive groups\" with respiratory issues. Meanwhile, the cities with the least amount of PM<sub>10</sub> were [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] and [[Malabon]], both with \"good\" amounts of 22 and 28 respectively. These were followed by \"moderate/fair\" amounts of PM<sub>10</sub> in [[Pasig]] (55), [[Para\u00f1aque]] (62) and [[Makati]] (63).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Acosta|first1=Renzo|title=Ashfall from Taal blast worsened air quality in some parts of NCR|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212548/ashfall-from-taal-blast-worsened-air-quality-in-some-parts-of-ncr|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114142429/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212548/ashfall-from-taal-blast-worsened-air-quality-in-some-parts-of-ncr|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy January 15, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that the slightly acidic lake which filled the main crater prior to the eruption had dried up, which was after confirmed by European satellite observations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Amos|first1=Jonathan|title=Taal volcano lake all but gone in eruption|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44661949|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=BBC News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> On January 28, the main crater emitted 800 meters of steam according to an 8 am bulletin by PHIVOLCS. It was described as a \"below instrumental detection\", while Alert Level 3 remained raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1220412/taal-volcano-emits-800-meters-high-of-white-to-dirty-steam-laden-plumes|title=Taal Volcano emits steam 800 meters high|last=Hallare|first=Katrina|date=January 28, 2020|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Seismic activity ===\n[[File:Taal volcano blanket ash ESA435812 - cropped.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Copernicus Programme|Copernicus]] [[Sentinel-2]] image of Taal Volcano on January 23, 2020, showing magmatic activity and the ash-blanketed towns of [[Agoncillo, Batangas|Agoncillo]] and [[Laurel, Batangas|Laurel]].]]\nOn February 13, 2020, the [[National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council]] (NDRRMC) and the [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]] (PHIVOLCS) have reported a total of 2,484 [[volcano tectonic earthquake]]s on the vicinity of the volcano since the eruption, 176 of which were felt.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\">{{cite web|title=NDRRMC Update: Situational Report No. 74 re Taal Volcano Phreatic Eruption|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/philippines/ndrrmc-update-situational-report-no-74-re-taal-volcano-eruption-13-february-2020|website=ndrrmc.gov.ph|publisher=National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The strongest were a series of {{M|w|4.1|link=y}} [[Moment magnitude scale|magnitude]] earthquakes originating {{convert|6|km|mi}} northwest of [[Agoncillo, Batangas]], which were recorded at least thrice: at 11:56{{nbsp}}pm on January 12, 3:11{{nbsp}}am on January 13, and 6:35{{nbsp}}am later that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Embudo|first1=Franz Lerwin|title=4.1 earthquake hits Batangas town near restive Taal|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/13/news/latest-stories/4-1-earthquake-hits-batangas-town-near-restive-taal/673852/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114170843/https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/13/news/latest-stories/4-1-earthquake-hits-batangas-town-near-restive-taal/673852/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, an Intensity III (\"weak\") on the [[PHIVOLCS Earthquake Intensity Scale]] was felt in [[Tagaytay]] and an Intensity II (\"slightly felt\") was felt in [[Malabon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tremors jolt Batangas, parts of Metro Manila|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/14/20/another-magnitude-40-volcanic-quake-hits-batangas|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114061014/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/14/20/another-magnitude-40-volcanic-quake-hits-batangas|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 11:39{{nbsp}}pm on January 13, 2020 and 5:50{{nbsp}}am the following day, PHIVOLCS reported a total of 44 earthquakes in the towns of [[Calaca, Batangas|Calaca]], [[Laurel, Batangas|Laurel]], [[Lemery, Batangas|Lemery]], [[Mataasnakahoy]], [[San Luis, Batangas|San Luis]], [[Taal, Batangas|Taal]] and Talisay in Batangas, and [[Alfonso, Cavite|Alfonso]] in Cavite; among the strongest were a magnitude {{M|w|3.6}} in Taal, which was felt at an Intensity III in Tagaytay,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lalu|first1=Gabriel Pabico|title=More than 40 quakes hound areas reeling from Taal Volcano's eruption|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212725/more-than-40-quakes-near-taal-volcano-after-magnitude-4-0-in-agoncillo-phivolcs|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155711/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212725/more-than-40-quakes-near-taal-volcano-after-magnitude-4-0-in-agoncillo-phivolcs|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a magnitude {{M|w|3.9}} originating {{convert|7|km|mi}} northeast of Talisay at 2:05{{nbsp}}am, measuring an Intensity IV (\"moderately strong\") in Tagaytay and Intensity II in Malabon and Pasay.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lalu|first1=Gabriel Pabico|title=Magnitude 3.9 volcanic quake hits Talisay, Batangas; Intensity IV felt in Tagaytay|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212675/magnitude-3-9-volcanic-quake-hits-talisay-batangas-intensity-iv-felt-in-tagaytay|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155947/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212675/magnitude-3-9-volcanic-quake-hits-talisay-batangas-intensity-iv-felt-in-tagaytay|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of these constant earthquakes, numerous [[Fissure vent|fissures]] or cracks appeared across different ''[[barangay]]s'' in the Batangas towns of Agoncillo, Lemery, San Nicolas, and Talisay, the towns within the 14-kilometer radius danger zone of Taal. A fissure also transected the road connecting Agoncillo to Laurel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php/taal-volcano-bulletin-menu/9642-taal-volcano-bulletin-15-january-2020-8-00-a-m|title=TAAL VOLCANO BULLETIN: 15 January 2020 8:00 A.M.|last=|first=|date=|website=DOST-PHIVOLCS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On January 15, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that the water in [[Taal Volcano Main Crater Lake|Main Crater Lake]] on Volcano Island have drained; the lake measured 1.9 kilometers wide and {{convert|4|m|ft}} above sea level. Portions of the [[Pansipit River]], had also drained as a result of \"the ground deformation caused by an upward movement of the [[magma]]\"; it was the same process that caused the series of earthquakes. PHIVOLCS have also hinted on underwater fissures in Taal Lake where the water may have drained into.<ref name=drained>{{cite news|last1=Cabico|first1=Gaea Katreena|title=Phivolcs: Taal's main crater lake has been drained|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1985075/phivolcs-taals-main-crater-lake-has-been-drained|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy January 27, 2020, from 5 am until January 28, 2020, only 3 volcanic earthquakes were recorded with magnitudes 1.5 to 2.2, with no felt event. As recorded by the [[United States Geological Survey]], 92 earthquakes were detected in the past 24 hours. Four of them are low frequency events, which are \"caused by cracks resonating as magma and gases move toward the surface\". PHIVOLCS also noted the low frequency events and they recorded 170 volcanic earthquakes in its 8 am bulletin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/250366-phivolcs-advisory-taal-volcano-status-january-28-2020|title=Taal sulfur dioxide, volcanic earthquakes go down further|last=Arceo|first=Acor|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and response==\n=== Local response ===\nOn January 13, 2020, the [[Batangas Provincial Board|provincial board of Batangas]] declared the province under a [[state of emergency|state of calamity]] following the eruption, ordering the evacuation of residents within a radius of {{convert|14|km|mi}} from the volcano.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249183-batangas-state-of-calamity-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|title=Batangas declares state of calamity due to Mayon Volcano eruption|last=Ganzon-Ozaeta|first=Tina|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092209/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249183-batangas-state-of-calamity-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] issued a situation report stating that an estimated number of 459,300 people are within the 14-kilometer danger zone;<ref>{{cite web|title=Philippines: Taal Volcano Eruption (As of 12 January 2020)|url=https://reliefweb.int/map/philippines/philippines-taal-volcano-eruption-12-january-2020|website=reliefweb.int|publisher=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|access-date=January 13, 2020|date=January 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205446/https://reliefweb.int/map/philippines/philippines-taal-volcano-eruption-12-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> charity organization [[Save the Children]] estimated that 21,000 of those are children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernando-Malipot|first1=Merlina|title=Charity group appeals for priority care for children|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/16/charity-group-appeals-for-priority-care-for-children/?doing_wp_cron=1579193035.4988338947296142578125|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> According to the NDRRMC situational report for January 18, 2020, a total of 16,174 families or 70,413 individuals are taking shelter in 300 evacuation centers.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/> These evacuation centers consist of over 140 schools across Batangas, [[Cavite]] and [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], according to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] (DepEd).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mateo|first1=Janvic|title=Schools near Taal to undergo inspection|url=https://www.philstar.com/other-sections/education-and-home/2020/01/16/1985287/schools-near-taal-undergo-inspection|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> A total of 96,061 people were affected and [[Power outage|electricity was cut]] in seven municipalities and cities across Batangas and Cavite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249171-evacuees-taal-volcano-eruption-january-13-2020|title=More than 24,000 people flee as Taal Volcano spews ash, lava|last=Gotinga|first=J. C.|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092321/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249171-evacuees-taal-volcano-eruption-january-13-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Talisay\u2013Tagaytay Road in Calabarzon was temporarily closed because of the evacuation of the residents. Heavy ashfall reduced visibility to near zero in some parts of the [[Santa Rosa\u2013Tagaytay Road]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721970/almost-zero-visibility-in-tagaytay-due-to-taal-unrest/story/|title=WATCH: Almost zero visibility in Tagaytay due to Taal unrest|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092213/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721970/almost-zero-visibility-in-tagaytay-due-to-taal-unrest/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] (DSWD) also stated that there are 5,000 family food packs and sleeping kits on the way for distribution to the evacuation centers.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721938/over-7-000-evacuated-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-activity-ndrrmc/story/|title=Over 7,000 evacuated in CALABARZON due to Taal activity \u2014NDRRMC|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092208/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721938/over-7-000-evacuated-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-activity-ndrrmc/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/13/1984457/ndrrmc-red-alert-over-taal-unrest|title=NDRRMC on red alert over Taal unrest|last=Luna|first=Franco|date=January 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092208/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/13/1984457/ndrrmc-red-alert-over-taal-unrest|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The DSWD and the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] (DOH) handed a combined total of {{Philippine peso|4.9 million|link=yes}} (US$96,656) worth of assistance to the affected residents in Calabarzon.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/> On January 15, 2020, Cavite Governor [[Jonvic Remulla]] declared the province under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esguerra|first1=Darryl John|title=Cavite now under state of calamity amid restive Taal Volcano|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213495/cavite-now-under-state-of-calamity-amid-restive-taal-volcano|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA state of calamity was declared in the whole [[Calabarzon]] region via ''Proclamation No. 906'' which was signed by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] on February 21. The declaration is set to last for one year unless lifted.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/727549/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption/story/ | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in CALABARZON due to Taal Volcano eruption | publisher=[[GMA News]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/27/1996493/duterte-places-taal-hit-calabarzon-under-state-calamity | title=Duterte places Taal-hit Calabarzon under state of calamity | publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/252842-duterte-declares-state-calamity-calabarzon-taal-volcano-unrest | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in Calabarzon due to Taal Volcano unrest | publisher=[[Rappler]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/27/20/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-eruption | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in Calabarzon due to Taal eruption | publisher=[[ABS CBN News]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nInterior Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]] directed the governors, mayors and local chief executives of [[Central Luzon]], the [[Metro Manila|National Capital Region]] and [[Southern Tagalog]] to convene their [[disaster risk reduction]] and management councils and instantly activate their [[incident management]] teams, [[network operations center]]s and other [[disaster response]] teams. The [[Department of the Interior and Local Government]] tasked the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) to deploy their disaster incident management task forces, reactionary standby forces and [[search and rescue]] units to the affected areas, while the [[Bureau of Fire Protection]] were tasked to assist the PNP and local government units in the mandatory evacuation of affected residents. A\u00f1o also urged the public to donate basic necessities to the victims through the local government units.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chavez|first1=Chito|title=DILG to locals execs in areas affected by Taal's eruption: Be physically present|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/dilg-to-locals-execs-in-areas-affected-by-taals-eruption-be-physically-present/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]], [[Philippine Air Force]] and [[Philippine Navy]] personnel have been dispatched to help the victims of the Taal volcano eruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212401/air-force-navy-rescue-units-to-help-taal-volcano-victims|title=Air Force, Navy rescue units to help Taal volcano victims|last=Jr|first=Delfin T. Mallari|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092157/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212401/air-force-navy-rescue-units-to-help-taal-volcano-victims|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090700|title=MMDA sends rescue team to Batangas for evacuation ops|last=Dela Cruz|first=Raymond|date=January 13, 2020|website=Philippine News Agency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092159/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090700|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image|total_width=260\n| direction         = vertical\n| image1            = Rodrigo Duterte meets Taal Volcano eruption victims (2020-01-14).jpg\n| caption1          = President Rodrigo Duterte addresses evacuees in Batangas City, January 14, 2020\n| image2            = \n| caption2          = Vice President Leni Robredo visits evacuees in Santa Teresita, Batangas, January 14, 2020\n}}\nPresident [[Rodrigo Duterte]], who was in [[Davao City]] during the eruption, ordered Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]] to suspend classes and government work in Calabarzon, Central Luzon and Metro Manila. President Duterte flew to Manila on the morning of January 13 and continued with his scheduled activities there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parrocha|first1=Azer|title=Duterte had difficulty flying back to Manila due to Taal unrest|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090691|access-date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114051007/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090691|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Duterte visited evacuees in [[Batangas City]] on January 14, 2020 and pledged to provide financial assistance worth {{Philippine peso|130 million}} ($2.6 million) to the affected residents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kabiling|first1=Genalyn|title=Duterte apologizes for late visit to Taal, assures victims of gov't aid|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/duterte-apologizes-for-late-visit-to-taal-assures-victims-of-govt-aid/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164714/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/duterte-apologizes-for-late-visit-to-taal-assures-victims-of-govt-aid/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He approved the recommendation of Defense Secretary [[Delfin Lorenzana]] to prohibit individuals from visiting or inhabiting the Taal island, declaring it a \"[[no man's land]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Valente|first1=Catherine S.|title=Duterte declares Taal Volcano island 'no man's land'|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/15/second-headline/duterte-declares-taal-volcano-island-no-mans-land/674495/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> While addressing evacuees in Batangas City, President Duterte also pushed for the construction of additional evacuation centers to be built \"simultaneously\" in disaster-prone areas during his administration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aguilar|first1=Krissy|title=Duterte wants more evacuation centers built before term ends|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213125/duterte-wants-more-evacuation-centers-built-before-term-ends|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114161831/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213125/duterte-wants-more-evacuation-centers-built-before-term-ends|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Concurrently, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] visited the municipalities of [[Santa Teresita, Batangas|Santa Teresita]] and [[San Jose, Batangas|San Jose]], and the city of [[Santo Tomas, Batangas|Santo Tomas]] in Batangas, where she helped distribute food packs and face masks to the affected residents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panti|first1=Llanesca|title=Robredo visits Batangas, office gives aid to those affected by Taal eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722140/robredo-visits-batangas-office-gives-aid-to-those-affected-by-taal-eruption/story/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114112354/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722140/robredo-visits-batangas-office-gives-aid-to-those-affected-by-taal-eruption/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Robredo stressed the lack of medicines, toilets, toiletries and sleeping mats being provided to them, other than food and water. She also requested local officials to prepare an inventory of the damage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duterte, Robredo make separate visits to Taal evacuees|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/14/duterte-robredo-visit-taal-evacuees.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114180050/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/14/duterte-robredo-visit-taal-evacuees.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the eruption, several members of the [[Senate of the Philippines|Philippine Senate]] called for more action from government institutions in assisting the victims. [[Joel Villanueva]] urged the [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] to issue an advisory that would guide private firms in the affected areas on deciding whether their operations should continue, considering the health and safety of its employees. Villanueva called on employers and designated safety officers to assess the safety conditions of the workplaces.<ref>{{cite web|title=Villanueva asks DOLE to issue labor advisory for workers following Taal eruption, ash fall|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_villanueva1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Imee Marcos]] urged the DOH and the [[Barangay Health Volunteers]] to prioritize providing [[clinical audit]]s to all evacuees for them to easily access [[Health care in the Philippines|medical health care]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congress must provide health audits to the evacuees - Imee|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0116_marcosi1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=Filipino|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Francis Pangilinan]] urged the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] to provide long-term funding assistance and initiate [[Alternative Livelihood|alternative livelihood]] programs for the affected farmers and farmworkers. Pangilinan also urged the establishment of [[Area of refuge|refuge areas]] for the pets of evacuees, as well as rescued stray animals from the affected areas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alternative livelihood, funding assistance for Taal-affected farmers, fisherfolk: Pangilinan|url=https://kikopangilinan.com/2020/01/15/alternative-livelihood-funding-assistance-for-taal-affected-farmers-fisherfolk-pangilinan/|publisher=Office of Senator Kiko Pangilinan|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Nancy Binay]] and [[Risa Hontiveros]] called on the DOH and DSWD to include [[N95 mask]]s, the prescribed mask for cases of volcanic ash, and other protective equipment in the provision of relief goods.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nancy to DOH, DSWD: Include masks in relief packages|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_binay1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Akbayan Senator Risa Hontiveros urging the provision of face masks and protective equipment to first responders and the vulnerable and sick|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_hontiveros1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Hontiveros also urged the DOH to provide [[mental health]] services, such as access to therapists, to victims who may have been traumatized by the disaster.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torregoza|first1=Hannah|title=Hontiveros calls for mental health support for families affected by Taal eruption|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/19/hontiveros-calls-for-mental-health-support-for-families-affected-by-taal-eruption/|access-date=January 19, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> On January 16, Cavite-based Senator [[Bong Revilla]] participated in the distribution of relief goods in several towns of his home province, which had been placed under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite web|title=More aid for Taal evacuees needed- Revilla|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0116_revilla1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Some senators also proposed for additional measures to be implemented in the wake of the eruption. Senate President [[Tito Sotto]] proposed [[cloud seeding]] as a method to clear the fallen ash and debris.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramos|first1=Christia Marie|title=Sotto wants cloud seeding in areas affected by Taal eruption, ashfall|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212574/sotto-wants-cloud-seeding-in-areas-affected-by-taal-eruption-ashfall|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114174708/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212574/sotto-wants-cloud-seeding-in-areas-affected-by-taal-eruption-ashfall|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials from PHIVOLCS and [[PAGASA]], however, rejected the proposal fearing that cloud seeding may result in [[acid rain]] or [[lahar]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Malasig|first1=Jenine|title=Why Filipinos did not welcome Tito Sotto's cloud seeding proposal to ashfall-stricken areas|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/01/14/160211/why-filipinos-did-not-welcome-tito-sottos-cloud-seeding-proposal-ashfall-stricken-areas-taal-volcano/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=InterAksyon|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> [[Sherwin Gatchalian]] urged the [[Congress of the Philippines|Philippine Congress]] to pass an additional budget of {{Philippine peso|10 billion}} ($196.4 million) to the nation's existing calamity budget, as at least {{Philippine peso|35 billion}} ($687.9 million) is at stake from the damages caused by the eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Legaspi|first1=Amita|title=P10-B supplemental budget needed to aid Taal victims \u2014Gatchalian|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722437/p10-b-supplemental-budget-needed-to-aid-taal-victims-gatchalian/story/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]], House Speaker [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] ([[Legislative district of Pateros\u2013Taguig|Pateros\u2013Taguig]]) directed [[Legislative districts of Leyte#4th District|Leyte 4th district]] representative [[Lucy Torres Gomez]], chairperson of the House Committee on Disaster Management, to collaborate with other relevant committees, government agencies and urban planning experts in composing a short-term and long-term comprehensive rehabilitation plan for the affected areas.<ref>{{cite news|title=House to help develop rehab plans for provinces hit by Taal eruption|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213599/house-to-help-develop-rehab-plans-for-provinces-hit-by-taal-eruption|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Legislative districts of Cavite#4th District|Cavite 4th district]] representative [[Elpidio Barzaga Jr.]] filed House Resolution 643, ordering the House to conduct an investigation on the lack of warning from PHIVOLCS regarding the imminent eruption. Barzaga stated that PHIVOLCS had issued an Alert Level 1 on Taal Volcano (indicating a \"slight increase in volcanic activity\") since March 2019, but he claimed that it failed to properly disseminate information to the public. The resolution also probes the presence of permanent settlements in the Taal island, despite the PHIVOLCS having already declared the island a \"permanent danger zone\". House Majority Leader [[Martin Romualdez]] ([[Legislative districts of Leyte#1st District|Leyte 1st district]]), however, defended PHIVOLCS by implying the difficulty in predicting the occurrence of volcanic eruptions. Romualdez added that the House allotted to PHIVOLCS an additional {{Philippine peso|221.4 million}} ($4.3 million) in order to reform \"the country's monitoring and warning program for volcanic eruption.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Porcalla|first1=Delon|title=House to probe Phivolcs' lack of warning on Taal|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1984949/house-probe-phivolcs-lack-warning-taal|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSenator [[Grace Poe]] and [[Legislative districts of Albay#2nd District|Albay 2nd district]] representative [[Joey Salceda]] pushed Congress to immediately pass the Department of Disaster Resilience (DDR) Bill to create the said department, an [[Executive departments of the Philippines|executive department]] responsible for disaster response and [[emergency management]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Santos|first1=Ana P.|title='No man's land': Philippines volcano displaced fear future|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/man-land-philippines-volcano-displaced-fear-future-200114234444635.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Al Jazeera|date=January 15, 2020|quote=Grace Poe, an independent senator, on Tuesday reiterated her call for the creation of the Department of Disaster Resilience and Emergency Management which would streamline the different components of emergency response under one government body.}}</ref> Poe illustrated that the DDR would place the existing NDRRMC under its organizational structure and create three new bureaus (disaster resiliency, disaster preparation and response, and knowledge management and dissemination).<ref>{{cite web|title=Poe urges immediate creation of Disaster Management Department|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1032838|publisher=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Salceda criticized the government's current system of disaster response mobilization that requires a \"time consuming and confusing\" inter-agency coordination, adding that the creation of the DDR would resolve these issues by \"unifying the different functions\" to ensure the efficiency of disaster relief goods and personnel.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cervantes|first1=Filane Mikee|title=Rehab plan for Taal-hit areas may cost P60-B: solon|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1091069|access-date=January 17, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral provinces have contributed humanitarian aid to the affected residents. The [[Pampanga|provincial government of Pampanga]] has sent aid, totaling in 8,500 food packs, plus teams of medical personnel, social workers, and search and rescue personnel for deployment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/survivors-of-pinatubo-eruption-send-aid-to-victims-of-taal-eruption|title=Survivors of Pinatubo eruption send aid to victims of Taal eruption|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113145648/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/survivors-of-pinatubo-eruption-send-aid-to-victims-of-taal-eruption/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, city governments across [[Metro Manila]] have also contributed aid, ranging from in-kind donations, toiletries, food packs, N95 masks and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249330-local-governments-outside-batangas-give-aid-victims-taal-volcano-eruptions-january-2020|title=Local governments outside Batangas give aid to Taal Volcano eruption victims|last=Tuquero|first=Loreben|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165412/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249330-local-governments-outside-batangas-give-aid-victims-taal-volcano-eruptions-january-2020|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other local governments soon pitched help, including the provincial governments of [[Quirino]] and [[Bulacan]], which donated food packs and medical supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1214166/more-luzon-lgus-send-donations-to-taal-volcano-victims|title=More Luzon LGUs send donations to Taal volcano victims|last=Jr|first=Carmela Reyes-Estrope, Tonette Orejas, Villamor Visaya|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, farmers and traders in the provinces of [[Benguet]] and [[Nueva Vizcaya]] donated vegetables to the Taal victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/722425/benguet-farmers-donate-vegetables-to-taal-victims/story/|title=IN PHOTOS: Benguet farmers donate vegetables to Taal victims|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gomez|first1=Eireene Jairee|title=Agri losses from Taal blasts reach P3.06B|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/18/news/national/agri-losses-from-taal-blasts-reach-p3-06b/675385/|access-date=January 19, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> The autonomous regional government of [[Bangsamoro]] also sent {{Philippine peso|2 million}}-worth of food and non-food items as aid.<ref name=\"mindanewsbarmm\">{{cite news|last1=Cabrera|first1=Ferdinandh|title=BARMM sends help to Taal victims|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/01/barmm-sends-help-to-taal-victims/|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=Minda News|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe fanbase of pop singer [[Sarah Geronimo]] organized a charity public event at [[Luneta Park]] in Manila on January 18 where attendees participate in a [[flash mob]] of the viral \"[[Tala (song)|Tala]]\" dance challenge.<ref>{{cite news|last1=San Juan|first1=Ratziel|title='Tala' for Taal: How you can dance to help Taal Volcano victims|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/01/17/1985347/tala-taal-how-you-can-dance-help-taal-volcano-victims|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> The proceeds for participating in the event would be forwarded to the [[Philippine Red Cross]] for donations to the eruption victims.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alegre|first1=Dianara|title=LOOK: Popsters to hold 'Tala para sa Taal' charity flash mob to help victims of Taal eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/celebritylife/hobbies/58419/look-popsters-to-hold-tala-para-sa-taal-charity-flash-mob-to-help-victims-of-taal-eruption/story|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of the Philippines]] will open its own map data of the volcano from 2014 to 2017 through its UP Training Center for Applied Geodesy and Photogrammetry to the public to speed up the rehabilitation of the affected areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/28/up-to-open-map-data-of-taal-volcano-to-the-public|title=UP to open map data of Taal Volcano to the public|last=Nazario|first=Dhel|date=January 28, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nYouTuber [[The Hungry Syrian Wanderer]] distributed face masks and also cook meals to the victims ahead to the eruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.mb.com.ph/2020/01/20/syrian-vlogger-distributes-meals-for-taal-evacuees/|title=Syrian vlogger distributes meals for Taal evacuees|author=Gabriela Baron|date=January 20, 2020|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Casualties ===\nA total of 39 people died as a result of the latest unrest in Taal, although only one reported case was directly from the eruption of January 12.  According to the [[Manila Bulletin]], people either perished because they refused to follow the evacuation order or decided to return to their homes, or died in the evacuation centers of heart attacks caused by anxiety <ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/39-deaths-recorded-during-taal-volcanos-eruption/|title=39 deaths recorded during Taal Volcano\u2019s eruption |publisher=Manila Bulletin|first=Aaron|last=Recuenco|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n=== Economic ===\n[[File:\u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05e8\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea_\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05d0\u05e8_2020._\u05d6\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05ea_\u05de\u05de\u05d8\u05d5\u05e1_\u05e0\u05d5\u05e1\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd.jpg|thumb|left|View of the eruption from an airplane]]\n[[File:Taal Volcano Island ashfall.png|thumb|Houses at a portion of the Taal Volcano island destroyed by ashfall.]]\nDemand for N95 masks increased rapidly, with some stores inflating its prices to {{Philippine peso|200}} ($3.95) a piece from the standard {{Philippine peso|25}}\u201340 ($0.49\u20130.79).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249132-face-masks-out-of-stock-stores-taal-volcano-ashfall-spreads-january-2020|title=Stores run out of face masks as Taal Volcano ash spreads to Calabarzon, Metro Manila|last=Rappler.com|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113011316/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249132-face-masks-out-of-stock-stores-taal-volcano-ashfall-spreads-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/721948/demand-for-n95-masks-up-after-ashfall-from-taal-volcano/story/|title=Demand for N95 masks up after ashfall from Taal Volcano|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113060918/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/721948/demand-for-n95-masks-up-after-ashfall-from-taal-volcano/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI) dispatched teams to monitor and observe the movement of retail prices in the market and warned businesses against raising the prices for higher profit margins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/01/13/1984488/dti-orders-crackdown-businesses-raising-face-mask-prices|title=DTI orders crackdown on businesses raising face mask prices|last=Cigaral|first=Ian Nicolas|date=January 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092211/https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/01/13/1984488/dti-orders-crackdown-businesses-raising-face-mask-prices|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> After DTI inspection, Trade Undersecretary Ruth Castelo commented that some medical establishments were selling 'fake' N95 masks, some of which are not medical-grade, and could still let in large foreign air particulates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/not-even-medical-grade-trade-department-warns-vs-fake-n95-masks|title='Not even medical grade': Trade department warns vs fake N95 masks|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165206/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/not-even-medical-grade-trade-department-warns-vs-fake-n95-masks|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the outcome of surprise inspections and consumer complaints, DTI has imposed notices of violation to 12 of the 17 stores that were inspected in Bambang, [[Manila]], citing that these businesses will be charged with administrative and criminal cases for violating the Consumer Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/15/dti-12-manila-establishments-charged-with-profiteering-on-n95-masks|title=DTI: 12 Manila establishments charged with profiteering on N95 masks|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] threatened to revoke the permits of medical supplies chains in the city involved in the price hike of face masks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Isko wants explanation from firms which hiked prices of N95 masks amid ashfall|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/722036/isko-wants-explanation-from-firms-which-hiked-prices-of-n95-masks-amid-ashfall/story/|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023832/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/722036/isko-wants-explanation-from-firms-which-hiked-prices-of-n95-masks-amid-ashfall/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mercury Drug]], a major pharmaceutical chain, pledged to replenish supply for the masks where prices would remain steady and that it would not hoard the supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/mercurydrugph/photos/a.207951849348417/1955757594567825/?type=3&refsrc=http://news.abs-cbn.com/|title=Mercury Drug Corporation|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=m.facebook.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/mercury-drug-replenishing-face-mask-supply-says-to-keep-price-unchanged|title=Mercury Drug replenishing face mask supply, says to keep price unchanged|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113060918/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/mercury-drug-replenishing-face-mask-supply-says-to-keep-price-unchanged|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The Department of Health imposed [[price controls]] on health-related goods, including face masks, to protect consumers from profiteering and hoarding.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Unite|first1=Betheena Kae|title=DoH orders price freeze on medicines|url=http://tempo.com.ph/2020/01/15/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medicines/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Tempo|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> The DOH mandates that the prices of N95 masks, in particular, should range between {{Philippine peso|45}}\u2013105 ($0.89\u20132.07).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gulla|first1=Vivienne|title=DOH orders price freeze on medical supplies in areas hit by Taal eruption|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medical-supplies-in-areas-hit-by-taal-eruption|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165439/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medical-supplies-in-areas-hit-by-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] suspended trading following the eruption on January 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/pse-trading-canceled-monday-due-to-taal-eruption|title=Stocks, currency spot trading canceled Monday due to Taal eruption|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114115911/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/pse-trading-canceled-monday-due-to-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PhStockExchange/status/1216479101982142464|title=Please be advised that there will be no trading at PSE, no clearing and settlement at the Securities Clearing Corporation of the Philippines today, January 13, 2020, to ensure the safety of employees and traders in light of the volcanic ash emission of Taal Volcano.|author=Phil. Stock Exchange|publisher=Twitter|date=January 12, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205434/https://mobile.twitter.com/PhStockExchange/status/1216479101982142464|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] (DA) reported that the damage to crops caused by the eruption are estimated to be {{Philippine peso|3.06 billion}} ($60.1 million), covering {{convert|2,722|ha|km2}} that includes 1,967 animals. Fisheries in the Taal Lake, consisting of about 6,000 [[Fish farming#Cage system|fish cages]] to capture a total of 15,033 metric tons of fish, suffered losses of {{Philippine peso|1.6 billion}} ($31.4 million). ''[[Kapeng barako]]'' and ''[[Coffea liberica]]'' crops, major products of Batangas and Cavite, have damages worth at least {{Philippine peso|360.5 million}} ($7.08 million) for 8,240 metric tons and {{convert|748|ha|acre}} of land. Pineapple plantations in the Cavite towns of [[Amadeo, Cavite|Amadeo]], [[Silang, Cavite|Silang]] and [[General Trias, Cavite|General Trias]] lost 21,079 metric tons of pineapple worth {{Philippine peso|527.25 million}} ($10.4 million). [[Rice production in the Philippines|Rice crops]] in {{convert|308|ha|acre}} of fields across Calabarzon were lost, amounting to {{Philippine peso|5.6 million}} ($109,985), while 5,329 metric tons of corn placed losses at {{Philippine peso|88.9 million}} ($1.7 million). The Philippine Crop Insurance Corporation reassured around 1,200 farmers and fishermen in Batangas that they are insured of a three-year zero-interest survival and recovery loan worth {{Philippine peso|25,000}} ($494.13) each, to be provided by the Mount Carmel Rural Bank.<ref>{{cite news|title=Farmers hit by Taal ashfall need aid, not loans|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/14/1984793/farmers-hit-taal-ashfall-need-aid-not-loans|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114113909/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/14/1984793/farmers-hit-taal-ashfall-need-aid-not-loans|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The DA plans to distribute materials and mechanisms for crop and livestock intervention worth {{Philippine peso|160 million}} ($3.1 million), which includes 5,000 [[coffea]] [[mother plant]]s and 1,000 [[cocoa bean]] seedlings from the [[Bureau of Plant Industry (Philippines)|Bureau of Plant Industry]], to 17 local government units in Batangas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cabuenas|first1=Jon Viktor|title=P577M worth of crops damaged by Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/722145/p577m-worth-of-crops-damaged-by-taal-volcano-eruption/story/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114110213/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/722145/p577m-worth-of-crops-damaged-by-taal-volcano-eruption/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Philippine Carabao Center]] and National Dairy Authority delivered {{convert|1|t|gr}} of corn [[silage]]s and {{convert|1.5|t|gr}} of [[rice straw]]s, a total of {{convert|2.5|t|gr}} of [[dietary fiber]], to Batangas.<ref name=\"agri losses\"/><ref name=\"agri losses\">{{cite news|title=Agri damage from Taal eruption reaches Php3B|url=http://www.da.gov.ph/agri-damage-from-taal-eruption-reaches-php3b/|access-date=January 21, 2020|work=da.gov.ph|publisher=Department of Agriculture|date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA [[brickworks]] in [[Bi\u00f1an]], Laguna used the ash spewed from Taal to manufacture hollow blocks and bricks. Through a combination of ash, sand, cement and discarded plastic waste, around 5,000 bricks are manufactured a day and are used to rebuild houses and other buildings that were damaged by the eruption. Bi\u00f1an Mayor Arman Dimaguila formally instructed residents in the city to help gather ashes and deliver it to the local brickworks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Philippines: Taal volcano residents turn ash and plastic waste into bricks|url=https://www.dw.com/en/philippines-taal-volcano-residents-turn-ash-and-plastic-waste-into-bricks/a-52050588|access-date=January 19, 2020|agency=Agence France-Presse and Reuters|via=Deutsche Welle|date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Smart Communications|Smart]] and [[Globe Telecom|Globe]] offered free calls and internet services and charging stations for those affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/249189-globe-smart-provide-free-calls-internet-victims-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|title=Globe, Smart offer free calls, internet for Taal Volcano eruption victims|last=Rivas|first=Ralf|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092301/https://www.rappler.com/business/249189-globe-smart-provide-free-calls-internet-victims-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Water concessionaire [[Manila Water]], in cooperation with Batangas Provincial Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office, sent a convoy of 30 water tankers to various evacuation centers in Batangas. The company is also sending an initial 2,000 five-gallon units of bottled water.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/287017/ayala-mobilizes-relief-efforts-amid-taal-eruption|title=Ayala mobilizes relief efforts amid Taal eruption|last=Dumlao-Abadilla|first=Doris|website=business.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113081142/https://business.inquirer.net/287017/ayala-mobilizes-relief-efforts-amid-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Meralco]], the country's leading power distributor, assembled [[Solar power|solar-powered]] mobile charging stations at various evacuation centers across [[Cavite]].<ref>{{cite news|title=One Meralco Foundation offers free charging, food packs to Taal Volcano victims|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/183111/one-meralco-foundation-offers-free-charging-food-packs-to-taal-volcano-victims|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[PhilPost]] announced on January 16 that it would suspend delivery and acceptance of mail in Batangas towns near the Taal Volcano which falls within the \"danger zone\".<ref>{{cite news|title=PHLPost suspends mail service in towns near Taal, volcano danger zone|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/16/20/phlpost-suspends-mail-service-in-towns-near-taal-volcano-danger-zone|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nThe Department of Health advised the public to remain indoors and minimize outdoor activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/01/13/taal-update-doh-issues-health-reminders-as-ashfall-envelops-luzon/|title=TAAL UPDATE: DOH issues health reminders as ashfall envelops Luzon {{!}} Claudeth Mocon-Ciriaco|last=Mocon-Ciriaco|first=Claudeth|date=January 13, 2020|website=BusinessMirror|language=en-US|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113023039/https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/01/13/taal-update-doh-issues-health-reminders-as-ashfall-envelops-luzon/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They also advised the public to refrain from purchasing and consuming [[freshwater fish]] from the Taal Lake, such as [[tilapia]] and ''[[Sardinella tawilis]]'', as these may have been affected by the sulfur from the eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merez|first1=Arianne|title=Don't eat fish from Taal Lake, DOH says|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/dont-eat-fish-from-taal-lake-doh-says|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114110456/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/dont-eat-fish-from-taal-lake-doh-says|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAgriculture Secretary [[William Dar]] clarified that fruits and vegetables filled with ash, including the ''[[Coffea liberica]]'' fruits that are homegrown in Batangas and Cavite, are safely consumable upon cleansing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ash-covered fruits, veggies still safe to eat after washing \u2013 DOH|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/15/taal-volcano-fruits-veggies-safe-to-eat.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Air traffic ===\n[[File:Hmw-Taal-2020112-2020113.gif|thumb|left|300px|[[NASA]] animation of the volcanic plume released by Taal from January 12\u201313, 2020, using data from [[Japan Meteorological Agency|JMA]]'s [[Himawari 8]] satellite. The eruption disrupted several flights to and from the Luzon island.]]\nOn January 12, 2020, the [[Manila International Airport Authority]] (MIAA) suspended all flights to and from all terminals of the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] (NAIA) in [[Manila]] following the eruption due to the [[Volcanic ash and aviation safety|various hazardous effects of volcanic ash on flight safety]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|title=Taal eruption puts NAIA flights on hold|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The MIAA recorded that at least 516 flights from and to NAIA were suspended, with about 80,000 passengers affected.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Ariel|title=80,000 passengers affected by NAIA closure|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/80000-passengers-affected-by-naia-closure/|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205306/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/80000-passengers-affected-by-naia-closure/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 13, operations at NAIA resumed partially from 10{{nbsp}}am onwards, although many flights still remained canceled or delayed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arayata|first1=Maria Cristina|title=NAIA resumes partial ops as runway clearing continues|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090701|access-date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205301/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090701|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of international flights bound for NAIA were diverted to either [[Clark International Airport]] in [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles]], [[Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport]], [[Haneda Airport]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Hong Kong International Airport]], or [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]] in [[Guam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=LIST: Flight cancellations due to Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/13/LIST-cancelled-flights-Monday-Taal.html|access-date=January 17, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> By January 14, 604 flights were canceled according to the NDRRMC. However, by January 15, 537 of those flights had resumed operations.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/>\n\nThe [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] advised the Luzon International Premiere Airport Development Corporation to suspend flights at Clark International Airport as reports indicate that ash could reach the area.<ref>{{cite news|title=NAIA flights canceled due to Taal ash explosion, Clark to be told to shut down too|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/12/20/naia-flights-put-on-hold-due-to-taal-ash-explosion|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> On January 13, only ten flights were reported to have been canceled, while nine flights were delayed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Cathrine|title=LIST: Canceled Clark flights on Monday, January 13, 2020|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212231/fwd-list-more-cancelled-flights-on-monday-january-13|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport (MCIA), only 25 domestic flights (all bound for NAIA) and one international flight were canceled, all of which were on January 14. However, the MCIA had to accommodate five international flights bound for NAIA that were diverted. The GMR\u2013Megawide Cebu Airport Corporation (GMCAC), the operator of the MCIA, requested that all diverted flights should be accommodated on a \"first-come, first-serve basis\" depending on the availability of [[Airport apron|aircraft parking bays]]. Aside from hotel bookings, passengers of the diverted flights were given small food packs. MCIA provided passengers with free bus services for inter-airport transfers and city hotel transfers. Retail stores and food concessionaires at the airport terminals immediately restocked their supply and offered discounts for passengers, available from January 12 to 14.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Israel|first1=Dale|title=Cebu airport cancels 26 flights, hosts 4 diverted intl flights due to Taal|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212814/cebu-airport-cancels-26-flights-hosts-4-diverted-intl-flights-due-to-taal|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\nCollegiate leagues, the [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] (UAAP)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atencio|first1=Peter|title=UAAP, NCAA cancel games|url=https://manilastandard.net/sports/sports-plus/314886/uaap-ncaa-cancel-games.html|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Standard|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> and the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association (Philippines)|National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) postponed games to be held in [[Metro Manila]] on January 13, 2020 due to ash fall. The junior basketball and junior football ties were to be held by the UAAP and volleyball games for the NCAA.<ref name=\"ncaavolley\">{{cite news|title=NCAA volleyball: Games called off due to Taal volcano effects|url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/ncaa-volleyball-games-called-off-due-to-taal-volcano-effects/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] match between [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] and [[Shan United F.C.|Shan United]] scheduled for January 14, 2020 at the [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]] in Manila was threatened to be postponed due to ash fall the day before but match officials decided that game should push through.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tupas|first1=Cedelf|title=Ceres battles Shan in knockout first round|url=https://sports.inquirer.net/381273/ceres-battles-shan-in-knockout-first-round|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nThe Philippine government, while it said that it would accept any international aid, has stated that it will not actively seek for foreign aid believing that it still has the capability to deal with the Taal Volcano eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esguerra|first1=Darryl John|title=Palace: Amid Taal Volcano eruption, PH won't ask for foreign help yet|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1214037/fwd-palace-ph-wont-ask-foreign-assistance-yet-for-taal-eruption|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[China Coast Guard]] donated 600 pieces of N95 masks, food packs, and other relief goods to evacuees in Batangas through the [[Philippine Coast Guard]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dela Cruz|first1=Raymond Carl|title=PCG receives relief goods for Taal eruption victims|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090813|access-date=January 16, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Agency for International Development]] and its [[Volcano Disaster Assistance Program]], through the [[Embassy of the United States, Manila|U.S. Embassy in the Philippines]], is providing [[thermographic camera]]s and remote technical support to assist the Philippine government in monitoring Taal's volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adel|first1=Rosette|title=USAID is helping Philippine government to monitor Taal eruption|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1985076/usaid-helping-philippine-government-monitor-taal-eruption|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[South Korea]] has also pledged US$200,000 in humanitarian aid through the Philippine Red Cross.<ref>{{cite news|title=S. Korea pledges US$200,000 in aid to Filipino victims of volcanic eruption|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200116007700325?input=fb|access-date=January 16, 2020|agency=Yonhap News Agency|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> The [[Singapore Red Cross]] on their part relayed about [[Singaporean dollar|S$]]67,000-worth of humanitarian aid to support the operations of their Philippine counterpart.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Clara|title=Singapore Red Cross gives $67,000 to victims of Taal volcano, launches public appeal for donations|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-red-cross-gives-67000-to-victims-of-taal-volcano-launches-public-appeal-for|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=New Strait Times|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> The [[Emirates Red Crescent]] also sent a delegation to the Philippines to assist on the relief operations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gibbon|first1=Gavin|title=UAE joins in aid mission to help victims of Taal Volcano in the Philippines|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/culture-society/438293-uae-joins-in-aid-mission-to-help-victims-of-taal-volcano-in-the-philippines|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=Arabian Business|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmerican comedian [[Dave Chappelle]], who visited Manila during the eruption, donated {{Philippine peso|1 million}} ($19,671) to the relief efforts for the eruption victims through the Rayomar Outreach Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sampayan|first1=Jacs|title=Comedian Dave Chappelle just donated PHP 1 million to the Taal rescue efforts|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/01/16/20/comedian-dave-chappelle-just-donated-php-1-million-to-the-taal-rescue-efforts|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]], through its Acute Large Emergency Response Tool (ALERT), has donated {{Philippine peso|42 million|link=yes}} ({{Euro|750 thousand|link=yes}}) in humanitarian aid which includes emergency shelter, psychosocial support services including child protection services and essential household items.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Neil Arwin Mercado|title=European Union donates P42M for Taal eruption victims|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1222339/european-union-donates-p42m-for-taal-eruption-victims|access-date=January 31, 2020|publisher=Inquirer News|date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=EU donates P42 million to families hit by Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/31/20/eu-donates-p42-million-to-families-hit-by-taal-volcano-eruption|access-date=January 31, 2020|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|2020 Taal Volcano eruptions}}\n{{Portal|Philippines|Volcanoes}}\n* {{ReliefWeb-link|vo-2020-000002-phl}}\n\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taal Volcano}}\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:21st-century volcanic events]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Volcanic eruptions in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Phreatic eruptions]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in the Philippines]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Volcanic eruption in the Philippines}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox eruption\n| name = 2020 Taal Volcano eruption\n| image = Taal Volcano - 12 January 2020.jpg\n| image_size = 280px\n| caption = Taal Volcano's January 12, 2020 explosion\n| start_date = January 12, 2020\n| start_time = \n| end_date = January 19, 2020 <br /> (decreased volcanic activity still ongoing)\n| volcano = [[Taal Volcano]]\n| type = Mainly Phreatomagmatic\n| location = [[Batangas]], [[Calabarzon]], Philippines\n| VEI = <!--wait for USGS / PHIVOLCS assessment-->\n| coordinates = {{coord|14|00|38|N|120|59|52|E|display=inline}}\n| map = Taal Volcano Danger Zone.svg\n| map_size = \n| map_caption = Map of Batangas highlighting the areas under the 14-kilometer radius danger zone\n| impact = 39 dead (only 1 direct, 38 indirect) <ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/39-deaths-recorded-during-taal-volcanos-eruption/|title=39 deaths recorded during Taal Volcano\u2019s eruption |publisher=Manila Bulletin|first=Aaron|last=Recuenco|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> \n}}\nThe eruption of [[Taal Volcano]] in [[Batangas]], [[Philippines]] on January 12, 2020, was a [[phreatic eruption]] from its main crater that spewed ashes across [[Calabarzon]], [[Metro Manila]], and some parts of [[Central Luzon]] and [[Ilocos Region]], resulting to the suspension of classes, work schedules, and flights in the area.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211934/list-class-suspensions-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption|title=LIST: Class suspensions due to Taal Volcano eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114132427/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211934/list-class-suspensions-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|title=Taal eruption puts NAIA flights on hold|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]] (PHIVOLCS) subsequently issued an Alert Level 4, indicating \"that a hazardous [[explosive eruption]] is possible within hours to days.\"<ref name=\"Manila Bulletin\">{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/12/alert-level-3-raised-as-taal-volcano-manifests-steam-driven-explosion/|title=Alert Level 3 raised as Taal volcano manifests steam-driven explosion|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112084337/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/12/alert-level-3-raised-as-taal-volcano-manifests-steam-driven-explosion/|archive-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|title=PHIVOLCS warns of 'hazardous explosive eruption' of Taal Volcano soon|website=cnn|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023853/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy January 26, 2020, PHIVOLCS observed an inconsistent, but decreasing volcanic activity in Taal, prompting the agency to downgrade its warning to Alert Level 3.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/scitech/science/723567/phivolcs-lowers-taal-volcano-alert-level-to-alert-level-3/story/?amp|title=PHIVOLCS lowers Taal Volcano's status to Alert Level 2|publisher=GMA News|first=Erwin|last=Colcol|date=January 26, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> It was until February 14, 2020, when PHIVOLCS finally decided to downgrade the volcano's warning to Alert Level 2, due to consistent decreased volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/725980/phivolcs-lowers-taal-volcano-s-status-to-alert-level-2/story/|title=PHIVOLCS lowers Taal Volcano's status to Alert Level 2|publisher=GMA News|first=Dona|last=Magsino|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/2/14/Taal-Volcano-alert-level-2.html|title=Taal Volcano status lowered to Alert Level 2|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=February 14, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Volcanic activity ==\n{{update section|date=January 2020}}\n\n=== Eruption ===\n[[File:Taal volcano 2020 eruption captured using IP camera.gif|upright=1.27|thumb|right|Phreatic explosion captured at the main crater of Taal Volcano. Video taken from the installed [[IP camera]] of PHIVOLCS monitoring Taal Volcano]]\n\nThe volcano erupted on the afternoon of January 12, 2020, 43 years after its [[Taal Volcano#1965 to 1977 eruption|previous eruption in 1977]].<ref name=\"Manila Bulletin\"/> According to PHIVOLCS director Dr. Renato Solidum,  seismic swarms began at 11 am and were later followed by [[phreatic eruption]] from Volcano Island Main Crater at around 1{{nbsp}}pm [[Philippine Standard Time]] ([[UTC+8]]).<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211871/taal-volcano-erupts|title=BREAKING: Taal volcano spews ash in phreatic eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113142821/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211871/taal-volcano-erupts|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Loud rumbling sounds were also felt and heard from the volcano island. By 2:30{{nbsp}}pm, PHIVOLCS raised the alert status to Alert Level 2, although PHIVOLCS through its Taal Volcano Observatory had advised residents of Volcano Island to evacuate at around 1 pm. {{nbsp}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/12/1984179/phivolcs-hoists-alert-level-2-over-taal-volcano-after-eruption|title=Phivolcs raises alert level to 3 as Taal Volcano spews kilometer-high plumes|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=PhilStar|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113125554/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/12/1984179/phivolcs-hoists-alert-level-2-over-taal-volcano-after-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Stronger explosions began by around 3{{nbsp}}pm that spewed an ash column exceeding a kilometer high, prompting PHIVOLCS to upgrade the alert status to Alert Level 3 by 4{{nbsp}}pm.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/249103-taal-volcano-phreatic-explosion-january-12-2020|title=Taal Volcano spews ash column 100 meters high|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Rappler]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113034450/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249103-taal-volcano-phreatic-explosion-january-12-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721885/pyroclastic-density-currents-volcanic-tsunami-likely-around-taal-phivolcs/story/|title=Pyroclastic density currents, volcanic tsunami likely around Taal \u2013PHIVOLCS|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721885/pyroclastic-density-currents-volcanic-tsunami-likely-around-taal-phivolcs/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Furthermore, Solidum confirmed that there was a [[Intrusive rock|magmatic intrusion]] that is likely the cause of the volcano's phreatic eruptions on Sunday morning and afternoon. PHIVOLCS advised evacuation of the towns of [[Balete, Batangas|Balete]], [[San Nicolas, Batangas|San Nicolas]], and [[Talisay, Batangas|Talisay]] in [[Batangas]] and other towns within the shores of [[Taal Lake]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/12/20/taal-volcano-erupts-as-phivolcs-raises-alert-level-2|title=Residents flee Taal island, as volcano spouts giant ash column|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114030350/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/12/20/taal-volcano-erupts-as-phivolcs-raises-alert-level-2|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|title=Evacuations underway as PHIVOLCS raises Alert Level 3 over Taal Volcano|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[CNN Philippines]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023853/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/12/PHIVOLCS-Taal-Volcano-explosion.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> By 7:30{{nbsp}}pm, PHIVOLCS upgraded the alert status to Alert Level 4 after volcanic activities intensified as \"continuous eruption generated a tall {{convert|10|to|15|km|mi}} steam-laden [[tephra]] column with frequent [[volcanic lightning]] that rained wet [[Ash fall|ashfall]] on the general north as far as [[Quezon City]] and [[Caloocan]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211988/taal-volcano-now-on-alert-level-4|title=Taal Volcano now on Alert Level 4|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer|Inquirer]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113151715/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211988/taal-volcano-now-on-alert-level-4|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Ashfall from the volcano were also experienced in [[Cavite]] and [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], and reached as far as Metro Manila and [[Pampanga]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211958/look-heavy-ashfall-in-batangas-cavite-laguna-after-taal-eruption|title=LOOK: Heavy ashfall in Batangas, Cavite, Laguna after Taal eruption|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113125343/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1211958/look-heavy-ashfall-in-batangas-cavite-laguna-after-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721903/ash-fall-from-taal-volcano-reaches-parts-of-metro-manila-ndrrmc/story/|title=Ash fall from Taal Volcano reaches parts of Metro Manila \u2014NDRRMC|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023832/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721903/ash-fall-from-taal-volcano-reaches-parts-of-metro-manila-ndrrmc/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2020/01/12/tens-of-thousands-evacuated-as-taal-volcano-violently-erupts-in-the-philippines/|title=Thousands evacuated as Taal Volcano violently erupts in the Philippines|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=New York Post|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205330/https://nypost.com/2020/01/12/tens-of-thousands-evacuated-as-taal-volcano-violently-erupts-in-the-philippines/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Phreatic_eruption_of_Taal_Volcano,_12_January_2020_(reduced).gif|thumb|right|Explosion seen from the Tagaytay City viewdeck]]\n\nOn January 13, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that activity in the Main Crater had transitioned into lava fountaining between 2:48{{nbsp}}am to 4:28{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.dwiz882am.com/index.php/bulkang-taal-nagbuga-ng-lava-fountain/|title=BULKANG TAAL NAGBUGA NG LAVA FOUNTAIN|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=[[DWIZ]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112221054/https://www.dwiz882am.com/index.php/bulkang-taal-nagbuga-ng-lava-fountain/|archive-date=January 12, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A [[Lava#Lava fountain|lava fountain]] was recorded at 3:20{{nbsp}}am.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212149/lava-fountain-from-taal-volcano|title=LOOK: Lava fountain from Taal Volcano|date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Inquirer.net|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205325/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212149/lava-fountain-from-taal-volcano|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Department of Environment and Natural Resources]] presented a study that the [[air quality index]] of cities in Metro Manila had worsened; [[Mandaluyong]] had the highest amount of inhalable [[PM10|coarse particulate matter]] (PM<sub>10</sub>) with 118, followed by [[Las Pi\u00f1as]] (108) and [[Taguig]] (104), all of which were \"considered unhealthy for sensitive groups\" with respiratory issues. Meanwhile, the cities with the least amount of PM<sub>10</sub> were [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] and [[Malabon]], both with \"good\" amounts of 22 and 28 respectively. These were followed by \"moderate/fair\" amounts of PM<sub>10</sub> in [[Pasig]] (55), [[Para\u00f1aque]] (62) and [[Makati]] (63).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Acosta|first1=Renzo|title=Ashfall from Taal blast worsened air quality in some parts of NCR|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212548/ashfall-from-taal-blast-worsened-air-quality-in-some-parts-of-ncr|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114142429/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212548/ashfall-from-taal-blast-worsened-air-quality-in-some-parts-of-ncr|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy January 15, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that the slightly acidic lake which filled the main crater prior to the eruption had dried up, which was after confirmed by European satellite observations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Amos|first1=Jonathan|title=Taal volcano lake all but gone in eruption|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-44661949|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=BBC News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> On January 28, the main crater emitted 800 meters of steam according to an 8 am bulletin by PHIVOLCS. It was described as a \"below instrumental detection\", while Alert Level 3 remained raised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1220412/taal-volcano-emits-800-meters-high-of-white-to-dirty-steam-laden-plumes|title=Taal Volcano emits steam 800 meters high|last=Hallare|first=Katrina|date=January 28, 2020|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Seismic activity ===\n[[File:Taal volcano blanket ash ESA435812 - cropped.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Copernicus Programme|Copernicus]] [[Sentinel-2]] image of Taal Volcano on January 23, 2020, showing magmatic activity and the ash-blanketed towns of [[Agoncillo, Batangas|Agoncillo]] and [[Laurel, Batangas|Laurel]].]]\nOn February 13, 2020, the [[National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council]] (NDRRMC) and the [[Philippine Institute of Volcanology and Seismology]] (PHIVOLCS) have reported a total of 2,484 [[volcano tectonic earthquake]]s on the vicinity of the volcano since the eruption, 176 of which were felt.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\">{{cite web|title=NDRRMC Update: Situational Report No. 74 re Taal Volcano Phreatic Eruption|url=https://reliefweb.int/report/philippines/ndrrmc-update-situational-report-no-74-re-taal-volcano-eruption-13-february-2020|website=ndrrmc.gov.ph|publisher=National Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Council|date=February 13, 2020|access-date=February 14, 2020}}</ref> The strongest were a series of {{M|w|4.1|link=y}} [[Moment magnitude scale|magnitude]] earthquakes originating {{convert|6|km|mi}} northwest of [[Agoncillo, Batangas]], which were recorded at least thrice: at 11:56{{nbsp}}pm on January 12, 3:11{{nbsp}}am on January 13, and 6:35{{nbsp}}am later that day.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Embudo|first1=Franz Lerwin|title=4.1 earthquake hits Batangas town near restive Taal|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/13/news/latest-stories/4-1-earthquake-hits-batangas-town-near-restive-taal/673852/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114170843/https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/13/news/latest-stories/4-1-earthquake-hits-batangas-town-near-restive-taal/673852/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> As a result, an Intensity III (\"weak\") on the [[PHIVOLCS Earthquake Intensity Scale]] was felt in [[Tagaytay]] and an Intensity II (\"slightly felt\") was felt in [[Malabon]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tremors jolt Batangas, parts of Metro Manila|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/14/20/another-magnitude-40-volcanic-quake-hits-batangas|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114061014/https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/14/20/another-magnitude-40-volcanic-quake-hits-batangas|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Between 11:39{{nbsp}}pm on January 13, 2020 and 5:50{{nbsp}}am the following day, PHIVOLCS reported a total of 44 earthquakes in the towns of [[Calaca, Batangas|Calaca]], [[Laurel, Batangas|Laurel]], [[Lemery, Batangas|Lemery]], [[Mataasnakahoy]], [[San Luis, Batangas|San Luis]], [[Taal, Batangas|Taal]] and Talisay in Batangas, and [[Alfonso, Cavite|Alfonso]] in Cavite; among the strongest were a magnitude {{M|w|3.6}} in Taal, which was felt at an Intensity III in Tagaytay,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lalu|first1=Gabriel Pabico|title=More than 40 quakes hound areas reeling from Taal Volcano's eruption|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212725/more-than-40-quakes-near-taal-volcano-after-magnitude-4-0-in-agoncillo-phivolcs|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155711/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212725/more-than-40-quakes-near-taal-volcano-after-magnitude-4-0-in-agoncillo-phivolcs|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> and a magnitude {{M|w|3.9}} originating {{convert|7|km|mi}} northeast of Talisay at 2:05{{nbsp}}am, measuring an Intensity IV (\"moderately strong\") in Tagaytay and Intensity II in Malabon and Pasay.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lalu|first1=Gabriel Pabico|title=Magnitude 3.9 volcanic quake hits Talisay, Batangas; Intensity IV felt in Tagaytay|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212675/magnitude-3-9-volcanic-quake-hits-talisay-batangas-intensity-iv-felt-in-tagaytay|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114155947/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212675/magnitude-3-9-volcanic-quake-hits-talisay-batangas-intensity-iv-felt-in-tagaytay|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of these constant earthquakes, numerous [[Fissure vent|fissures]] or cracks appeared across different ''[[barangay]]s'' in the Batangas towns of Agoncillo, Lemery, San Nicolas, and Talisay, the towns within the 14-kilometer radius danger zone of Taal. A fissure also transected the road connecting Agoncillo to Laurel.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.phivolcs.dost.gov.ph/index.php/taal-volcano-bulletin-menu/9642-taal-volcano-bulletin-15-january-2020-8-00-a-m|title=TAAL VOLCANO BULLETIN: 15 January 2020 8:00 A.M.|last=|first=|date=|website=DOST-PHIVOLCS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On January 15, 2020, PHIVOLCS reported that the water in [[Taal Volcano Main Crater Lake|Main Crater Lake]] on Volcano Island have drained; the lake measured 1.9 kilometers wide and {{convert|4|m|ft}} above sea level. Portions of the [[Pansipit River]], had also drained as a result of \"the ground deformation caused by an upward movement of the [[magma]]\"; it was the same process that caused the series of earthquakes. PHIVOLCS have also hinted on underwater fissures in Taal Lake where the water may have drained into.<ref name=drained>{{cite news|last1=Cabico|first1=Gaea Katreena|title=Phivolcs: Taal's main crater lake has been drained|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1985075/phivolcs-taals-main-crater-lake-has-been-drained|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nBy January 27, 2020, from 5 am until January 28, 2020, only 3 volcanic earthquakes were recorded with magnitudes 1.5 to 2.2, with no felt event. As recorded by the [[United States Geological Survey]], 92 earthquakes were detected in the past 24 hours. Four of them are low frequency events, which are \"caused by cracks resonating as magma and gases move toward the surface\". PHIVOLCS also noted the low frequency events and they recorded 170 volcanic earthquakes in its 8 am bulletin.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/250366-phivolcs-advisory-taal-volcano-status-january-28-2020|title=Taal sulfur dioxide, volcanic earthquakes go down further|last=Arceo|first=Acor|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Impact and response==\n=== Local response ===\nOn January 13, 2020, the [[Batangas Provincial Board|provincial board of Batangas]] declared the province under a [[state of emergency|state of calamity]] following the eruption, ordering the evacuation of residents within a radius of {{convert|14|km|mi}} from the volcano.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249183-batangas-state-of-calamity-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|title=Batangas declares state of calamity due to Mayon Volcano eruption|last=Ganzon-Ozaeta|first=Tina|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092209/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249183-batangas-state-of-calamity-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[United Nations Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs]] issued a situation report stating that an estimated number of 459,300 people are within the 14-kilometer danger zone;<ref>{{cite web|title=Philippines: Taal Volcano Eruption (As of 12 January 2020)|url=https://reliefweb.int/map/philippines/philippines-taal-volcano-eruption-12-january-2020|website=reliefweb.int|publisher=UN Office for the Coordination of Humanitarian Affairs|access-date=January 13, 2020|date=January 12, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205446/https://reliefweb.int/map/philippines/philippines-taal-volcano-eruption-12-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> charity organization [[Save the Children]] estimated that 21,000 of those are children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hernando-Malipot|first1=Merlina|title=Charity group appeals for priority care for children|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/16/charity-group-appeals-for-priority-care-for-children/?doing_wp_cron=1579193035.4988338947296142578125|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> According to the NDRRMC situational report for January 18, 2020, a total of 16,174 families or 70,413 individuals are taking shelter in 300 evacuation centers.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/> These evacuation centers consist of over 140 schools across Batangas, [[Cavite]] and [[Laguna (province)|Laguna]], according to the [[Department of Education (Philippines)|Department of Education]] (DepEd).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mateo|first1=Janvic|title=Schools near Taal to undergo inspection|url=https://www.philstar.com/other-sections/education-and-home/2020/01/16/1985287/schools-near-taal-undergo-inspection|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> A total of 96,061 people were affected and [[Power outage|electricity was cut]] in seven municipalities and cities across Batangas and Cavite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249171-evacuees-taal-volcano-eruption-january-13-2020|title=More than 24,000 people flee as Taal Volcano spews ash, lava|last=Gotinga|first=J. C.|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092321/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249171-evacuees-taal-volcano-eruption-january-13-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The Talisay\u2013Tagaytay Road in Calabarzon was temporarily closed because of the evacuation of the residents. Heavy ashfall reduced visibility to near zero in some parts of the [[Santa Rosa\u2013Tagaytay Road]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721970/almost-zero-visibility-in-tagaytay-due-to-taal-unrest/story/|title=WATCH: Almost zero visibility in Tagaytay due to Taal unrest|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092213/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721970/almost-zero-visibility-in-tagaytay-due-to-taal-unrest/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] (DSWD) also stated that there are 5,000 family food packs and sleeping kits on the way for distribution to the evacuation centers.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721938/over-7-000-evacuated-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-activity-ndrrmc/story/|title=Over 7,000 evacuated in CALABARZON due to Taal activity \u2014NDRRMC|last=Bajo|first=Anna Felicia|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092208/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/721938/over-7-000-evacuated-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-activity-ndrrmc/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/13/1984457/ndrrmc-red-alert-over-taal-unrest|title=NDRRMC on red alert over Taal unrest|last=Luna|first=Franco|date=January 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092208/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/13/1984457/ndrrmc-red-alert-over-taal-unrest|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The DSWD and the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] (DOH) handed a combined total of {{Philippine peso|4.9 million|link=yes}} (US$96,656) worth of assistance to the affected residents in Calabarzon.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/> On January 15, 2020, Cavite Governor [[Jonvic Remulla]] declared the province under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esguerra|first1=Darryl John|title=Cavite now under state of calamity amid restive Taal Volcano|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213495/cavite-now-under-state-of-calamity-amid-restive-taal-volcano|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA state of calamity was declared in the whole [[Calabarzon]] region via ''Proclamation No. 906'' which was signed by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] on February 21. The declaration is set to last for one year unless lifted.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/727549/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-volcano-eruption/story/ | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in CALABARZON due to Taal Volcano eruption | publisher=[[GMA News]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/02/27/1996493/duterte-places-taal-hit-calabarzon-under-state-calamity | title=Duterte places Taal-hit Calabarzon under state of calamity | publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/252842-duterte-declares-state-calamity-calabarzon-taal-volcano-unrest | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in Calabarzon due to Taal Volcano unrest | publisher=[[Rappler]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/02/27/20/duterte-declares-state-of-calamity-in-calabarzon-due-to-taal-eruption | title=Duterte declares state of calamity in Calabarzon due to Taal eruption | publisher=[[ABS CBN News]] | date=February 27, 2020 | accessdate=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nInterior Secretary [[Eduardo A\u00f1o]] directed the governors, mayors and local chief executives of [[Central Luzon]], the [[Metro Manila|National Capital Region]] and [[Southern Tagalog]] to convene their [[disaster risk reduction]] and management councils and instantly activate their [[incident management]] teams, [[network operations center]]s and other [[disaster response]] teams. The [[Department of the Interior and Local Government]] tasked the [[Philippine National Police]] (PNP) to deploy their disaster incident management task forces, reactionary standby forces and [[search and rescue]] units to the affected areas, while the [[Bureau of Fire Protection]] were tasked to assist the PNP and local government units in the mandatory evacuation of affected residents. A\u00f1o also urged the public to donate basic necessities to the victims through the local government units.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chavez|first1=Chito|title=DILG to locals execs in areas affected by Taal's eruption: Be physically present|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/dilg-to-locals-execs-in-areas-affected-by-taals-eruption-be-physically-present/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]], [[Philippine Air Force]] and [[Philippine Navy]] personnel have been dispatched to help the victims of the Taal volcano eruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212401/air-force-navy-rescue-units-to-help-taal-volcano-victims|title=Air Force, Navy rescue units to help Taal volcano victims|last=Jr|first=Delfin T. Mallari|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092157/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212401/air-force-navy-rescue-units-to-help-taal-volcano-victims|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090700|title=MMDA sends rescue team to Batangas for evacuation ops|last=Dela Cruz|first=Raymond|date=January 13, 2020|website=Philippine News Agency|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092159/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090700|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image|total_width=260\n| direction         = vertical\n| image1            = Rodrigo Duterte meets Taal Volcano eruption victims (2020-01-14).jpg\n| caption1          = President Rodrigo Duterte addresses evacuees in Batangas City, January 14, 2020\n| image2            = \n| caption2          = Vice President Leni Robredo visits evacuees in Santa Teresita, Batangas, January 14, 2020\n}}\nPresident [[Rodrigo Duterte]], who was in [[Davao City]] during the eruption, ordered Executive Secretary [[Salvador Medialdea]] to suspend classes and government work in Calabarzon, Central Luzon and Metro Manila. President Duterte flew to Manila on the morning of January 13 and continued with his scheduled activities there.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Parrocha|first1=Azer|title=Duterte had difficulty flying back to Manila due to Taal unrest|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090691|access-date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114051007/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090691|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Duterte visited evacuees in [[Batangas City]] on January 14, 2020 and pledged to provide financial assistance worth {{Philippine peso|130 million}} ($2.6 million) to the affected residents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kabiling|first1=Genalyn|title=Duterte apologizes for late visit to Taal, assures victims of gov't aid|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/duterte-apologizes-for-late-visit-to-taal-assures-victims-of-govt-aid/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114164714/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/14/duterte-apologizes-for-late-visit-to-taal-assures-victims-of-govt-aid/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> He approved the recommendation of Defense Secretary [[Delfin Lorenzana]] to prohibit individuals from visiting or inhabiting the Taal island, declaring it a \"[[no man's land]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Valente|first1=Catherine S.|title=Duterte declares Taal Volcano island 'no man's land'|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/15/second-headline/duterte-declares-taal-volcano-island-no-mans-land/674495/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> While addressing evacuees in Batangas City, President Duterte also pushed for the construction of additional evacuation centers to be built \"simultaneously\" in disaster-prone areas during his administration.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aguilar|first1=Krissy|title=Duterte wants more evacuation centers built before term ends|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213125/duterte-wants-more-evacuation-centers-built-before-term-ends|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 16, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114161831/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213125/duterte-wants-more-evacuation-centers-built-before-term-ends|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Concurrently, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] visited the municipalities of [[Santa Teresita, Batangas|Santa Teresita]] and [[San Jose, Batangas|San Jose]], and the city of [[Santo Tomas, Batangas|Santo Tomas]] in Batangas, where she helped distribute food packs and face masks to the affected residents.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Panti|first1=Llanesca|title=Robredo visits Batangas, office gives aid to those affected by Taal eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722140/robredo-visits-batangas-office-gives-aid-to-those-affected-by-taal-eruption/story/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114112354/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722140/robredo-visits-batangas-office-gives-aid-to-those-affected-by-taal-eruption/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Robredo stressed the lack of medicines, toilets, toiletries and sleeping mats being provided to them, other than food and water. She also requested local officials to prepare an inventory of the damage.<ref>{{cite news|title=Duterte, Robredo make separate visits to Taal evacuees|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/14/duterte-robredo-visit-taal-evacuees.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114180050/https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/14/duterte-robredo-visit-taal-evacuees.html|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the eruption, several members of the [[Senate of the Philippines|Philippine Senate]] called for more action from government institutions in assisting the victims. [[Joel Villanueva]] urged the [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] to issue an advisory that would guide private firms in the affected areas on deciding whether their operations should continue, considering the health and safety of its employees. Villanueva called on employers and designated safety officers to assess the safety conditions of the workplaces.<ref>{{cite web|title=Villanueva asks DOLE to issue labor advisory for workers following Taal eruption, ash fall|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_villanueva1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> [[Imee Marcos]] urged the DOH and the [[Barangay Health Volunteers]] to prioritize providing [[clinical audit]]s to all evacuees for them to easily access [[Health care in the Philippines|medical health care]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Congress must provide health audits to the evacuees - Imee|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0116_marcosi1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|language=Filipino|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> [[Francis Pangilinan]] urged the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] to provide long-term funding assistance and initiate [[Alternative Livelihood|alternative livelihood]] programs for the affected farmers and farmworkers. Pangilinan also urged the establishment of [[Area of refuge|refuge areas]] for the pets of evacuees, as well as rescued stray animals from the affected areas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alternative livelihood, funding assistance for Taal-affected farmers, fisherfolk: Pangilinan|url=https://kikopangilinan.com/2020/01/15/alternative-livelihood-funding-assistance-for-taal-affected-farmers-fisherfolk-pangilinan/|publisher=Office of Senator Kiko Pangilinan|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Nancy Binay]] and [[Risa Hontiveros]] called on the DOH and DSWD to include [[N95 mask]]s, the prescribed mask for cases of volcanic ash, and other protective equipment in the provision of relief goods.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nancy to DOH, DSWD: Include masks in relief packages|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_binay1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Statement of Akbayan Senator Risa Hontiveros urging the provision of face masks and protective equipment to first responders and the vulnerable and sick|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0113_hontiveros1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Hontiveros also urged the DOH to provide [[mental health]] services, such as access to therapists, to victims who may have been traumatized by the disaster.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Torregoza|first1=Hannah|title=Hontiveros calls for mental health support for families affected by Taal eruption|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/19/hontiveros-calls-for-mental-health-support-for-families-affected-by-taal-eruption/|access-date=January 19, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> On January 16, Cavite-based Senator [[Bong Revilla]] participated in the distribution of relief goods in several towns of his home province, which had been placed under a state of calamity.<ref>{{cite web|title=More aid for Taal evacuees needed- Revilla|url=https://www.senate.gov.ph/press_release/2020/0116_revilla1.asp|publisher=Senate of the Philippines|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Some senators also proposed for additional measures to be implemented in the wake of the eruption. Senate President [[Tito Sotto]] proposed [[cloud seeding]] as a method to clear the fallen ash and debris.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ramos|first1=Christia Marie|title=Sotto wants cloud seeding in areas affected by Taal eruption, ashfall|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212574/sotto-wants-cloud-seeding-in-areas-affected-by-taal-eruption-ashfall|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114174708/https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212574/sotto-wants-cloud-seeding-in-areas-affected-by-taal-eruption-ashfall|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Officials from PHIVOLCS and [[PAGASA]], however, rejected the proposal fearing that cloud seeding may result in [[acid rain]] or [[lahar]]s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Malasig|first1=Jenine|title=Why Filipinos did not welcome Tito Sotto's cloud seeding proposal to ashfall-stricken areas|url=http://www.interaksyon.com/politics-issues/2020/01/14/160211/why-filipinos-did-not-welcome-tito-sottos-cloud-seeding-proposal-ashfall-stricken-areas-taal-volcano/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=InterAksyon|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> [[Sherwin Gatchalian]] urged the [[Congress of the Philippines|Philippine Congress]] to pass an additional budget of {{Philippine peso|10 billion}} ($196.4 million) to the nation's existing calamity budget, as at least {{Philippine peso|35 billion}} ($687.9 million) is at stake from the damages caused by the eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Legaspi|first1=Amita|title=P10-B supplemental budget needed to aid Taal victims \u2014Gatchalian|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/722437/p10-b-supplemental-budget-needed-to-aid-taal-victims-gatchalian/story/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[House of Representatives of the Philippines|Philippine House of Representatives]], House Speaker [[Alan Peter Cayetano]] ([[Legislative district of Pateros\u2013Taguig|Pateros\u2013Taguig]]) directed [[Legislative districts of Leyte#4th District|Leyte 4th district]] representative [[Lucy Torres Gomez]], chairperson of the House Committee on Disaster Management, to collaborate with other relevant committees, government agencies and urban planning experts in composing a short-term and long-term comprehensive rehabilitation plan for the affected areas.<ref>{{cite news|title=House to help develop rehab plans for provinces hit by Taal eruption|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1213599/house-to-help-develop-rehab-plans-for-provinces-hit-by-taal-eruption|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Legislative districts of Cavite#4th District|Cavite 4th district]] representative [[Elpidio Barzaga Jr.]] filed House Resolution 643, ordering the House to conduct an investigation on the lack of warning from PHIVOLCS regarding the imminent eruption. Barzaga stated that PHIVOLCS had issued an Alert Level 1 on Taal Volcano (indicating a \"slight increase in volcanic activity\") since March 2019, but he claimed that it failed to properly disseminate information to the public. The resolution also probes the presence of permanent settlements in the Taal island, despite the PHIVOLCS having already declared the island a \"permanent danger zone\". House Majority Leader [[Martin Romualdez]] ([[Legislative districts of Leyte#1st District|Leyte 1st district]]), however, defended PHIVOLCS by implying the difficulty in predicting the occurrence of volcanic eruptions. Romualdez added that the House allotted to PHIVOLCS an additional {{Philippine peso|221.4 million}} ($4.3 million) in order to reform \"the country's monitoring and warning program for volcanic eruption.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Porcalla|first1=Delon|title=House to probe Phivolcs' lack of warning on Taal|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1984949/house-probe-phivolcs-lack-warning-taal|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSenator [[Grace Poe]] and [[Legislative districts of Albay#2nd District|Albay 2nd district]] representative [[Joey Salceda]] pushed Congress to immediately pass the Department of Disaster Resilience (DDR) Bill to create the said department, an [[Executive departments of the Philippines|executive department]] responsible for disaster response and [[emergency management]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Santos|first1=Ana P.|title='No man's land': Philippines volcano displaced fear future|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/01/man-land-philippines-volcano-displaced-fear-future-200114234444635.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Al Jazeera|date=January 15, 2020|quote=Grace Poe, an independent senator, on Tuesday reiterated her call for the creation of the Department of Disaster Resilience and Emergency Management which would streamline the different components of emergency response under one government body.}}</ref> Poe illustrated that the DDR would place the existing NDRRMC under its organizational structure and create three new bureaus (disaster resiliency, disaster preparation and response, and knowledge management and dissemination).<ref>{{cite web|title=Poe urges immediate creation of Disaster Management Department|url=https://pia.gov.ph/news/articles/1032838|publisher=Philippine Information Agency|access-date=January 17, 2020|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> Salceda criticized the government's current system of disaster response mobilization that requires a \"time consuming and confusing\" inter-agency coordination, adding that the creation of the DDR would resolve these issues by \"unifying the different functions\" to ensure the efficiency of disaster relief goods and personnel.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cervantes|first1=Filane Mikee|title=Rehab plan for Taal-hit areas may cost P60-B: solon|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1091069|access-date=January 17, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral provinces have contributed humanitarian aid to the affected residents. The [[Pampanga|provincial government of Pampanga]] has sent aid, totaling in 8,500 food packs, plus teams of medical personnel, social workers, and search and rescue personnel for deployment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/survivors-of-pinatubo-eruption-send-aid-to-victims-of-taal-eruption|title=Survivors of Pinatubo eruption send aid to victims of Taal eruption|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113145648/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/survivors-of-pinatubo-eruption-send-aid-to-victims-of-taal-eruption/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, city governments across [[Metro Manila]] have also contributed aid, ranging from in-kind donations, toiletries, food packs, N95 masks and others.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249330-local-governments-outside-batangas-give-aid-victims-taal-volcano-eruptions-january-2020|title=Local governments outside Batangas give aid to Taal Volcano eruption victims|last=Tuquero|first=Loreben|website=Rappler|language=en|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165412/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249330-local-governments-outside-batangas-give-aid-victims-taal-volcano-eruptions-january-2020|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Other local governments soon pitched help, including the provincial governments of [[Quirino]] and [[Bulacan]], which donated food packs and medical supplies.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1214166/more-luzon-lgus-send-donations-to-taal-volcano-victims|title=More Luzon LGUs send donations to Taal volcano victims|last=Jr|first=Carmela Reyes-Estrope, Tonette Orejas, Villamor Visaya|website=newsinfo.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> Meanwhile, farmers and traders in the provinces of [[Benguet]] and [[Nueva Vizcaya]] donated vegetables to the Taal victims.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/722425/benguet-farmers-donate-vegetables-to-taal-victims/story/|title=IN PHOTOS: Benguet farmers donate vegetables to Taal victims|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gomez|first1=Eireene Jairee|title=Agri losses from Taal blasts reach P3.06B|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/01/18/news/national/agri-losses-from-taal-blasts-reach-p3-06b/675385/|access-date=January 19, 2020|work=The Manila Times|date=January 18, 2020}}</ref> The autonomous regional government of [[Bangsamoro]] also sent {{Philippine peso|2 million}}-worth of food and non-food items as aid.<ref name=\"mindanewsbarmm\">{{cite news|last1=Cabrera|first1=Ferdinandh|title=BARMM sends help to Taal victims|url=https://www.mindanews.com/top-stories/2020/01/barmm-sends-help-to-taal-victims/|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=Minda News|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe fanbase of pop singer [[Sarah Geronimo]] organized a charity public event at [[Luneta Park]] in Manila on January 18 where attendees participate in a [[flash mob]] of the viral \"[[Tala (song)|Tala]]\" dance challenge.<ref>{{cite news|last1=San Juan|first1=Ratziel|title='Tala' for Taal: How you can dance to help Taal Volcano victims|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/01/17/1985347/tala-taal-how-you-can-dance-help-taal-volcano-victims|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 17, 2020}}</ref> The proceeds for participating in the event would be forwarded to the [[Philippine Red Cross]] for donations to the eruption victims.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Alegre|first1=Dianara|title=LOOK: Popsters to hold 'Tala para sa Taal' charity flash mob to help victims of Taal eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/entertainment/celebritylife/hobbies/58419/look-popsters-to-hold-tala-para-sa-taal-charity-flash-mob-to-help-victims-of-taal-eruption/story|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[University of the Philippines]] will open its own map data of the volcano from 2014 to 2017 through its UP Training Center for Applied Geodesy and Photogrammetry to the public to speed up the rehabilitation of the affected areas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/28/up-to-open-map-data-of-taal-volcano-to-the-public|title=UP to open map data of Taal Volcano to the public|last=Nazario|first=Dhel|date=January 28, 2020|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nYouTuber [[The Hungry Syrian Wanderer]] distributed face masks and also cook meals to the victims ahead to the eruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertainment.mb.com.ph/2020/01/20/syrian-vlogger-distributes-meals-for-taal-evacuees/|title=Syrian vlogger distributes meals for Taal evacuees|author=Gabriela Baron|date=January 20, 2020|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Casualties ===\nA total of 39 people died as a result of the latest unrest in Taal, although only one reported case was directly from the eruption of January 12.  According to the [[Manila Bulletin]], people either perished because they refused to follow the evacuation order or decided to return to their homes, or died in the evacuation centers of heart attacks caused by anxiety <ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/02/01/39-deaths-recorded-during-taal-volcanos-eruption/|title=39 deaths recorded during Taal Volcano\u2019s eruption |publisher=Manila Bulletin|first=Aaron|last=Recuenco|date=February 2, 2020|access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref>.\n\n=== Economic ===\n[[File:\u05d4\u05ea\u05e4\u05e8\u05e6\u05d5\u05ea_\u05d9\u05e0\u05d5\u05d0\u05e8_2020._\u05d6\u05d5\u05d5\u05d9\u05ea_\u05de\u05de\u05d8\u05d5\u05e1_\u05e0\u05d5\u05e1\u05e2\u05d9\u05dd.jpg|thumb|left|View of the eruption from an airplane]]\n[[File:Taal Volcano Island ashfall.png|thumb|Houses at a portion of the Taal Volcano island destroyed by ashfall.]]\nDemand for N95 masks increased rapidly, with some stores inflating its prices to {{Philippine peso|200}} ($3.95) a piece from the standard {{Philippine peso|25}}\u201340 ($0.49\u20130.79).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/249132-face-masks-out-of-stock-stores-taal-volcano-ashfall-spreads-january-2020|title=Stores run out of face masks as Taal Volcano ash spreads to Calabarzon, Metro Manila|last=Rappler.com|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113011316/https://www.rappler.com/nation/249132-face-masks-out-of-stock-stores-taal-volcano-ashfall-spreads-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/721948/demand-for-n95-masks-up-after-ashfall-from-taal-volcano/story/|title=Demand for N95 masks up after ashfall from Taal Volcano|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113060918/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/companies/721948/demand-for-n95-masks-up-after-ashfall-from-taal-volcano/story/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[Department of Trade and Industry (Philippines)|Department of Trade and Industry]] (DTI) dispatched teams to monitor and observe the movement of retail prices in the market and warned businesses against raising the prices for higher profit margins.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/01/13/1984488/dti-orders-crackdown-businesses-raising-face-mask-prices|title=DTI orders crackdown on businesses raising face mask prices|last=Cigaral|first=Ian Nicolas|date=January 13, 2020|website=philstar.com|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092211/https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/01/13/1984488/dti-orders-crackdown-businesses-raising-face-mask-prices|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> After DTI inspection, Trade Undersecretary Ruth Castelo commented that some medical establishments were selling 'fake' N95 masks, some of which are not medical-grade, and could still let in large foreign air particulates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/not-even-medical-grade-trade-department-warns-vs-fake-n95-masks|title='Not even medical grade': Trade department warns vs fake N95 masks|last=News|first=ABS-CBN|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|access-date=January 15, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165206/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/not-even-medical-grade-trade-department-warns-vs-fake-n95-masks|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Due to the outcome of surprise inspections and consumer complaints, DTI has imposed notices of violation to 12 of the 17 stores that were inspected in Bambang, [[Manila]], citing that these businesses will be charged with administrative and criminal cases for violating the Consumer Act.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/15/dti-12-manila-establishments-charged-with-profiteering-on-n95-masks|title=DTI: 12 Manila establishments charged with profiteering on N95 masks|website=Manila Bulletin News|language=en-US|access-date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[Manila]] Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] threatened to revoke the permits of medical supplies chains in the city involved in the price hike of face masks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Isko wants explanation from firms which hiked prices of N95 masks amid ashfall|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/722036/isko-wants-explanation-from-firms-which-hiked-prices-of-n95-masks-amid-ashfall/story/|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023832/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/722036/isko-wants-explanation-from-firms-which-hiked-prices-of-n95-masks-amid-ashfall/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Mercury Drug]], a major pharmaceutical chain, pledged to replenish supply for the masks where prices would remain steady and that it would not hoard the supply.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.facebook.com/mercurydrugph/photos/a.207951849348417/1955757594567825/?type=3&refsrc=http://news.abs-cbn.com/|title=Mercury Drug Corporation|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=m.facebook.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/mercury-drug-replenishing-face-mask-supply-says-to-keep-price-unchanged|title=Mercury Drug replenishing face mask supply, says to keep price unchanged|last=|first=|date=January 13, 2020|website=ABS-CBN News|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113060918/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/mercury-drug-replenishing-face-mask-supply-says-to-keep-price-unchanged|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The Department of Health imposed [[price controls]] on health-related goods, including face masks, to protect consumers from profiteering and hoarding.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Unite|first1=Betheena Kae|title=DoH orders price freeze on medicines|url=http://tempo.com.ph/2020/01/15/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medicines/|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=Tempo|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> The DOH mandates that the prices of N95 masks, in particular, should range between {{Philippine peso|45}}\u2013105 ($0.89\u20132.07).<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gulla|first1=Vivienne|title=DOH orders price freeze on medical supplies in areas hit by Taal eruption|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medical-supplies-in-areas-hit-by-taal-eruption|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114165439/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/doh-orders-price-freeze-on-medical-supplies-in-areas-hit-by-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] suspended trading following the eruption on January 13.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/pse-trading-canceled-monday-due-to-taal-eruption|title=Stocks, currency spot trading canceled Monday due to Taal eruption|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114115911/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/13/20/pse-trading-canceled-monday-due-to-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.twitter.com/PhStockExchange/status/1216479101982142464|title=Please be advised that there will be no trading at PSE, no clearing and settlement at the Securities Clearing Corporation of the Philippines today, January 13, 2020, to ensure the safety of employees and traders in light of the volcanic ash emission of Taal Volcano.|author=Phil. Stock Exchange|publisher=Twitter|date=January 12, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205434/https://mobile.twitter.com/PhStockExchange/status/1216479101982142464|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] (DA) reported that the damage to crops caused by the eruption are estimated to be {{Philippine peso|3.06 billion}} ($60.1 million), covering {{convert|2,722|ha|km2}} that includes 1,967 animals. Fisheries in the Taal Lake, consisting of about 6,000 [[Fish farming#Cage system|fish cages]] to capture a total of 15,033 metric tons of fish, suffered losses of {{Philippine peso|1.6 billion}} ($31.4 million). ''[[Kapeng barako]]'' and ''[[Coffea liberica]]'' crops, major products of Batangas and Cavite, have damages worth at least {{Philippine peso|360.5 million}} ($7.08 million) for 8,240 metric tons and {{convert|748|ha|acre}} of land. Pineapple plantations in the Cavite towns of [[Amadeo, Cavite|Amadeo]], [[Silang, Cavite|Silang]] and [[General Trias, Cavite|General Trias]] lost 21,079 metric tons of pineapple worth {{Philippine peso|527.25 million}} ($10.4 million). [[Rice production in the Philippines|Rice crops]] in {{convert|308|ha|acre}} of fields across Calabarzon were lost, amounting to {{Philippine peso|5.6 million}} ($109,985), while 5,329 metric tons of corn placed losses at {{Philippine peso|88.9 million}} ($1.7 million). The Philippine Crop Insurance Corporation reassured around 1,200 farmers and fishermen in Batangas that they are insured of a three-year zero-interest survival and recovery loan worth {{Philippine peso|25,000}} ($494.13) each, to be provided by the Mount Carmel Rural Bank.<ref>{{cite news|title=Farmers hit by Taal ashfall need aid, not loans|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/14/1984793/farmers-hit-taal-ashfall-need-aid-not-loans|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114113909/https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/14/1984793/farmers-hit-taal-ashfall-need-aid-not-loans|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The DA plans to distribute materials and mechanisms for crop and livestock intervention worth {{Philippine peso|160 million}} ($3.1 million), which includes 5,000 [[coffea]] [[mother plant]]s and 1,000 [[cocoa bean]] seedlings from the [[Bureau of Plant Industry (Philippines)|Bureau of Plant Industry]], to 17 local government units in Batangas.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Cabuenas|first1=Jon Viktor|title=P577M worth of crops damaged by Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/722145/p577m-worth-of-crops-damaged-by-taal-volcano-eruption/story/|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=GMA News Online|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114110213/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/money/economy/722145/p577m-worth-of-crops-damaged-by-taal-volcano-eruption/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[Philippine Carabao Center]] and National Dairy Authority delivered {{convert|1|t|gr}} of corn [[silage]]s and {{convert|1.5|t|gr}} of [[rice straw]]s, a total of {{convert|2.5|t|gr}} of [[dietary fiber]], to Batangas.<ref name=\"agri losses\"/><ref name=\"agri losses\">{{cite news|title=Agri damage from Taal eruption reaches Php3B|url=http://www.da.gov.ph/agri-damage-from-taal-eruption-reaches-php3b/|access-date=January 21, 2020|work=da.gov.ph|publisher=Department of Agriculture|date=January 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA [[brickworks]] in [[Bi\u00f1an]], Laguna used the ash spewed from Taal to manufacture hollow blocks and bricks. Through a combination of ash, sand, cement and discarded plastic waste, around 5,000 bricks are manufactured a day and are used to rebuild houses and other buildings that were damaged by the eruption. Bi\u00f1an Mayor Arman Dimaguila formally instructed residents in the city to help gather ashes and deliver it to the local brickworks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Philippines: Taal volcano residents turn ash and plastic waste into bricks|url=https://www.dw.com/en/philippines-taal-volcano-residents-turn-ash-and-plastic-waste-into-bricks/a-52050588|access-date=January 19, 2020|agency=Agence France-Presse and Reuters|via=Deutsche Welle|date=January 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Smart Communications|Smart]] and [[Globe Telecom|Globe]] offered free calls and internet services and charging stations for those affected.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rappler.com/business/249189-globe-smart-provide-free-calls-internet-victims-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|title=Globe, Smart offer free calls, internet for Taal Volcano eruption victims|last=Rivas|first=Ralf|date=January 13, 2020|website=Rappler|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113092301/https://www.rappler.com/business/249189-globe-smart-provide-free-calls-internet-victims-taal-volcano-eruption-january-2020|archive-date=January 13, 2020|access-date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> Water concessionaire [[Manila Water]], in cooperation with Batangas Provincial Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Office, sent a convoy of 30 water tankers to various evacuation centers in Batangas. The company is also sending an initial 2,000 five-gallon units of bottled water.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/287017/ayala-mobilizes-relief-efforts-amid-taal-eruption|title=Ayala mobilizes relief efforts amid Taal eruption|last=Dumlao-Abadilla|first=Doris|website=business.inquirer.net|language=en|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113081142/https://business.inquirer.net/287017/ayala-mobilizes-relief-efforts-amid-taal-eruption|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Meralco]], the country's leading power distributor, assembled [[Solar power|solar-powered]] mobile charging stations at various evacuation centers across [[Cavite]].<ref>{{cite news|title=One Meralco Foundation offers free charging, food packs to Taal Volcano victims|url=https://globalnation.inquirer.net/183111/one-meralco-foundation-offers-free-charging-food-packs-to-taal-volcano-victims|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[PhilPost]] announced on January 16 that it would suspend delivery and acceptance of mail in Batangas towns near the Taal Volcano which falls within the \"danger zone\".<ref>{{cite news|title=PHLPost suspends mail service in towns near Taal, volcano danger zone|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/16/20/phlpost-suspends-mail-service-in-towns-near-taal-volcano-danger-zone|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Health ===\nThe Department of Health advised the public to remain indoors and minimize outdoor activities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/01/13/taal-update-doh-issues-health-reminders-as-ashfall-envelops-luzon/|title=TAAL UPDATE: DOH issues health reminders as ashfall envelops Luzon {{!}} Claudeth Mocon-Ciriaco|last=Mocon-Ciriaco|first=Claudeth|date=January 13, 2020|website=BusinessMirror|language=en-US|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113023039/https://businessmirror.com.ph/2020/01/13/taal-update-doh-issues-health-reminders-as-ashfall-envelops-luzon/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> They also advised the public to refrain from purchasing and consuming [[freshwater fish]] from the Taal Lake, such as [[tilapia]] and ''[[Sardinella tawilis]]'', as these may have been affected by the sulfur from the eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Merez|first1=Arianne|title=Don't eat fish from Taal Lake, DOH says|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/dont-eat-fish-from-taal-lake-doh-says|access-date=January 14, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 14, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114110456/https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/14/20/dont-eat-fish-from-taal-lake-doh-says|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAgriculture Secretary [[William Dar]] clarified that fruits and vegetables filled with ash, including the ''[[Coffea liberica]]'' fruits that are homegrown in Batangas and Cavite, are safely consumable upon cleansing.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ash-covered fruits, veggies still safe to eat after washing \u2013 DOH|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/15/taal-volcano-fruits-veggies-safe-to-eat.html|access-date=January 15, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Air traffic ===\n[[File:Hmw-Taal-2020112-2020113.gif|thumb|left|300px|[[NASA]] animation of the volcanic plume released by Taal from January 12\u201313, 2020, using data from [[Japan Meteorological Agency|JMA]]'s [[Himawari 8]] satellite. The eruption disrupted several flights to and from the Luzon island.]]\nOn January 12, 2020, the [[Manila International Airport Authority]] (MIAA) suspended all flights to and from all terminals of the [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]] (NAIA) in [[Manila]] following the eruption due to the [[Volcanic ash and aviation safety|various hazardous effects of volcanic ash on flight safety]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|title=Taal eruption puts NAIA flights on hold|date=January 12, 2020|publisher=[[GMA News]]|access-date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200114023833/https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/721897/taal-eruption-puts-naia-flights-on-hold/story/|archive-date=January 14, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The MIAA recorded that at least 516 flights from and to NAIA were suspended, with about 80,000 passengers affected.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Ariel|title=80,000 passengers affected by NAIA closure|url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/80000-passengers-affected-by-naia-closure/|access-date=January 13, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205306/https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/80000-passengers-affected-by-naia-closure/|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On January 13, operations at NAIA resumed partially from 10{{nbsp}}am onwards, although many flights still remained canceled or delayed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Arayata|first1=Maria Cristina|title=NAIA resumes partial ops as runway clearing continues|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090701|access-date=January 13, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 13, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200113205301/https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090701|archive-date=January 13, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A number of international flights bound for NAIA were diverted to either [[Clark International Airport]] in [[Angeles, Philippines|Angeles]], [[Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport]], [[Haneda Airport]] in [[Tokyo]], [[Hong Kong International Airport]], or [[Antonio B. Won Pat International Airport]] in [[Guam]].<ref>{{cite news|title=LIST: Flight cancellations due to Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/1/13/LIST-cancelled-flights-Monday-Taal.html|access-date=January 17, 2020|publisher=CNN Philippines|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> By January 14, 604 flights were canceled according to the NDRRMC. However, by January 15, 537 of those flights had resumed operations.<ref name=\"NDRRMC\"/>\n\nThe [[Civil Aviation Authority of the Philippines]] advised the Luzon International Premiere Airport Development Corporation to suspend flights at Clark International Airport as reports indicate that ash could reach the area.<ref>{{cite news|title=NAIA flights canceled due to Taal ash explosion, Clark to be told to shut down too|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/business/01/12/20/naia-flights-put-on-hold-due-to-taal-ash-explosion|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 12, 2020}}</ref> On January 13, only ten flights were reported to have been canceled, while nine flights were delayed.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gonzales|first1=Cathrine|title=LIST: Canceled Clark flights on Monday, January 13, 2020|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212231/fwd-list-more-cancelled-flights-on-monday-january-13|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt the Mactan\u2013Cebu International Airport (MCIA), only 25 domestic flights (all bound for NAIA) and one international flight were canceled, all of which were on January 14. However, the MCIA had to accommodate five international flights bound for NAIA that were diverted. The GMR\u2013Megawide Cebu Airport Corporation (GMCAC), the operator of the MCIA, requested that all diverted flights should be accommodated on a \"first-come, first-serve basis\" depending on the availability of [[Airport apron|aircraft parking bays]]. Aside from hotel bookings, passengers of the diverted flights were given small food packs. MCIA provided passengers with free bus services for inter-airport transfers and city hotel transfers. Retail stores and food concessionaires at the airport terminals immediately restocked their supply and offered discounts for passengers, available from January 12 to 14.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Israel|first1=Dale|title=Cebu airport cancels 26 flights, hosts 4 diverted intl flights due to Taal|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1212814/cebu-airport-cancels-26-flights-hosts-4-diverted-intl-flights-due-to-taal|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Sports ===\nCollegiate leagues, the [[University Athletic Association of the Philippines]] (UAAP)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Atencio|first1=Peter|title=UAAP, NCAA cancel games|url=https://manilastandard.net/sports/sports-plus/314886/uaap-ncaa-cancel-games.html|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Standard|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref> and the [[National Collegiate Athletic Association (Philippines)|National Collegiate Athletic Association]] (NCAA) postponed games to be held in [[Metro Manila]] on January 13, 2020 due to ash fall. The junior basketball and junior football ties were to be held by the UAAP and volleyball games for the NCAA.<ref name=\"ncaavolley\">{{cite news|title=NCAA volleyball: Games called off due to Taal volcano effects|url=https://sports.mb.com.ph/2020/01/13/ncaa-volleyball-games-called-off-due-to-taal-volcano-effects/|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Manila Bulletin|date=January 13, 2020}}</ref> The [[2020 AFC Champions League|AFC Champions League]] match between [[Ceres\u2013Negros F.C.|Ceres\u2013Negros]] and [[Shan United F.C.|Shan United]] scheduled for January 14, 2020 at the [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]] in Manila was threatened to be postponed due to ash fall the day before but match officials decided that game should push through.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tupas|first1=Cedelf|title=Ceres battles Shan in knockout first round|url=https://sports.inquirer.net/381273/ceres-battles-shan-in-knockout-first-round|access-date=January 17, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== International response ===\nThe Philippine government, while it said that it would accept any international aid, has stated that it will not actively seek for foreign aid believing that it still has the capability to deal with the Taal Volcano eruption.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Esguerra|first1=Darryl John|title=Palace: Amid Taal Volcano eruption, PH won't ask for foreign help yet|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1214037/fwd-palace-ph-wont-ask-foreign-assistance-yet-for-taal-eruption|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[China Coast Guard]] donated 600 pieces of N95 masks, food packs, and other relief goods to evacuees in Batangas through the [[Philippine Coast Guard]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dela Cruz|first1=Raymond Carl|title=PCG receives relief goods for Taal eruption victims|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1090813|access-date=January 16, 2020|publisher=Philippine News Agency|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Agency for International Development]] and its [[Volcano Disaster Assistance Program]], through the [[Embassy of the United States, Manila|U.S. Embassy in the Philippines]], is providing [[thermographic camera]]s and remote technical support to assist the Philippine government in monitoring Taal's volcanic activity.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Adel|first1=Rosette|title=USAID is helping Philippine government to monitor Taal eruption|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/01/15/1985076/usaid-helping-philippine-government-monitor-taal-eruption|access-date=January 15, 2020|work=The Philippine Star|date=January 15, 2020}}</ref> [[South Korea]] has also pledged US$200,000 in humanitarian aid through the Philippine Red Cross.<ref>{{cite news|title=S. Korea pledges US$200,000 in aid to Filipino victims of volcanic eruption|url=https://en.yna.co.kr/view/AEN20200116007700325?input=fb|access-date=January 16, 2020|agency=Yonhap News Agency|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref> The [[Singapore Red Cross]] on their part relayed about [[Singaporean dollar|S$]]67,000-worth of humanitarian aid to support the operations of their Philippine counterpart.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Chong|first1=Clara|title=Singapore Red Cross gives $67,000 to victims of Taal volcano, launches public appeal for donations|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-red-cross-gives-67000-to-victims-of-taal-volcano-launches-public-appeal-for|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=New Strait Times|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> The [[Emirates Red Crescent]] also sent a delegation to the Philippines to assist on the relief operations.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gibbon|first1=Gavin|title=UAE joins in aid mission to help victims of Taal Volcano in the Philippines|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/culture-society/438293-uae-joins-in-aid-mission-to-help-victims-of-taal-volcano-in-the-philippines|access-date=January 22, 2020|work=Arabian Business|date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAmerican comedian [[Dave Chappelle]], who visited Manila during the eruption, donated {{Philippine peso|1 million}} ($19,671) to the relief efforts for the eruption victims through the Rayomar Outreach Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sampayan|first1=Jacs|title=Comedian Dave Chappelle just donated PHP 1 million to the Taal rescue efforts|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/ancx/culture/spotlight/01/16/20/comedian-dave-chappelle-just-donated-php-1-million-to-the-taal-rescue-efforts|access-date=January 16, 2020|work=ABS-CBN News|date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[European Union]], through its Acute Large Emergency Response Tool (ALERT), has donated {{Philippine peso|42 million|link=yes}} ({{Euro|750 thousand|link=yes}}) in humanitarian aid which includes emergency shelter, psychosocial support services including child protection services and essential household items.<ref>{{cite news|author1=Neil Arwin Mercado|title=European Union donates P42M for Taal eruption victims|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1222339/european-union-donates-p42m-for-taal-eruption-victims|access-date=January 31, 2020|publisher=Inquirer News|date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=EU donates P42 million to families hit by Taal Volcano eruption|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/31/20/eu-donates-p42-million-to-families-hit-by-taal-volcano-eruption|access-date=January 31, 2020|publisher=ABS-CBN News|date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|2020 Taal Volcano eruptions}}\n{{Portal|Philippines|Volcanoes}}\n* {{ReliefWeb-link|vo-2020-000002-phl}}\n\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taal Volcano}}\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Asia]]\n[[Category:2020 in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:2020 natural disasters]]\n[[Category:21st-century volcanic events]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Asia]]\n[[Category:Volcanic eruptions in the Philippines]]\n[[Category:Phreatic eruptions]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in the Philippines]]\n", "name_user": "178.167.195.10", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Taal_Volcano_eruption"}
{"title_page": "Adebola Adesola", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerian businesswoman}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2019}}\n'''Bola Adesola''' is an accountant in [[Federal Republic of Nigeria|Nigeria]]. She is the Senior Vice-Chairman at Standard Chartered Bank Group where she was previously the CEO of Standard Chartered Bank for Nigeria and West Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/standard-chartered-appoints-bola-adesola-as-senior-vice-chairman-africa/|title=Standard Chartered appoints Bola Adesola as Senior Vice Chairman, Africa|date=11 January 2019|publisher=|access-date=8 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329074435/https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/standard-chartered-appoints-bola-adesola-as-senior-vice-chairman-africa/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Adesola has over 25 years of experience in the banking sector.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thenationonlineng.net/standard-chartered-bank-appoints-nigeria-ceo/|title=Standard Chartered Bank appoints Nigeria CEO|date=27 December 2018|publisher=|access-date=31 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531015620/https://thenationonlineng.net/standard-chartered-bank-appoints-nigeria-ceo/|archive-date=31 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Education and career==\nAdesola graduated with a degree in law from  [[Buckingham University]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in 1984,  and was called to the  Nigerian Bar in 1985.  She started her professional life in corporate legal practice  until  1990. During the period of her life as legal practitioner, she  furthers her education towards accounting at Harvard  Business School. She studied Advanced Management Program.  In the 1990,  she started her practice  as  a  banker with the Citibank, Nigeria. There she  served for nine years until 1999 when she moved to [[First Bank of Nigeria]] due to the position of Managing Director of a  group of  eight banks led by the First Bank  of  Nigeria. First  Bank  of Nigeria happened to lead a group of  eight banks called the Kakawa Discount House Limited in the year 1995.  In  2005  she was  made the Managing Director, First Bank of Nigeria Plc (now FBN Holdings Plc) in charge of corporate banking after five year Bola Adesola resigns \nIn 2010 Adesola started working with the  [[Standard Chartered Bank Group]]. After six month of appointment with the  Standard Chartered Bank group Adesola was appointed the Managing Director then in the year 2013, Chief Executive Office of the bank group.  She had engaged in many activities around commerce and banking market while been the CEO of the bank  group. In 2019 she was made senior vice chairman of the Standard Chartered Bank group.<ref name=\"wimbiz.org\">{{cite web|url=https://wimbiz.org/members/bola-adesola/|title=Bola Adesola - WIMBIZ|publisher=|access-date=2019-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329074532/https://wimbiz.org/members/bola-adesola/|archive-date=2019-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sc.com/ng/about-us/management-committee.html|title=Management Committee - About Us - Standard Chartered Bank Nigeria|website=www.sc.com|access-date=2019-03-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329074530/https://www.sc.com/ng/about-us/management-committee.html|archive-date=2019-03-29|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and activities==\n\nFinancial  Markets Dealers Association  - Trustee and Executive Board Member <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fmdqotc.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/07/Annual-Report-final.pdf |title=Annual Report INNER 16 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=2019-05-31}}</ref><ref>https://www.fmdqotc.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Annual-Report-2017.pdf</ref>\nCentral Bank  of Nigeria Bankers\u2019 Committee on Economic Development, Sustainability and Gender - Chairperson \nUnited Nations Global Compact \u2013 Member, 2018 <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/sg/personnel-appointments/2018-04-20/ms-bola-adesola-nigeria-vice-chair-board-united-nations|title=Ms. Bola Adesola of Nigeria - Vice Chair of the Board of the United Nations Global Compact|date=20 April 2018|website=United Nations Secretary-General|access-date=11 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180725173018/https://www.un.org/sg/en/content/sg/personnel-appointments/2018-04-20/ms-bola-adesola-nigeria-vice-chair-board-united-nations|archive-date=25 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\nUnited Nations - Director, 2015 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://businessnews.com.ng/2015/07/20/standard-chartered-md-bola-adesola-joins-un-global-compact-board/|title=Standard Chartered MD, Bola Adesola joins UN Global Compact Board|date=20 July 2015|publisher=|access-date=11 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171026124217/http://businessnews.com.ng/2015/07/20/standard-chartered-md-bola-adesola-joins-un-global-compact-board/|archive-date=26 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://host424.hostmonster.com/suspended.page/disabled.cgi/www.cp-africa.com|title=This website is currently unavailable.|website=host424.hostmonster.com|access-date=2019-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190625175248/http://host424.hostmonster.com/suspended.page/disabled.cgi/www.cp-africa.com|archive-date=2019-06-25|url-status=live}}</ref>\nNigeria National Competitiveness Council  - Executive Member, 2013 \nLagos  Business School Alumni Association (LBSAA) - Vice President,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lbs.edu.ng/search/bola+adesola/|title=You searched for bola adesola|publisher=|access-date=2019-05-31|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190531015621/https://www.lbs.edu.ng/search/bola%2Badesola/|archive-date=2019-05-31|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WhtfDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA128&lpg=PA128&dq=bola+adesola+Financial++Markets+Dealers+Association&source=bl&ots=x-DfeAz0Wn&sig=ACfU3U2OFku5yZyzD3oGliQBCqYIizK4nQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiU7sqO7_jgAhWjsXEKHcIiCPI4ChDoATAFegQICRAB#v=onepage&q=bola+adesola+Financial++Markets+Dealers+Association&f=false|title=Alumni Leadership and University Excellence in Africa: The Case of Lagos Business School|first=Henry O.|last=Onukwuba|date=7 June 2018|publisher=Springer|via=Google Books}}</ref>\nFate Foundation - Board  Member <ref>{{cite web|url=https://fatefoundation.org/our_team/bola-adesola/|title=Bola Adesola - - FATE Foundation|publisher=}}</ref>\nWomen in Business and Management (WIMBIZ) - Co-founder and Former Chairperson, 2001<ref name=\"wimbiz.org\"/>\nAdvisory Board of Genevieve Magazine  - Member\nEditorial  Board of  Rubies Honorary Fellow \u2013 Member\nChartered Institute of Bankers Nigeria Recipient  (CIBN)\nAfrica Business Award, 2013 \nChartered Institute of Bankers Nigeria \u2013 Board  Member\nFinancial Markets Dealers Quotations Plc \u2013Board Member\nNigeria Inter-bank Settlement Systems Plc.- Board Member\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Buckingham]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Nigerian accountants]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerian businesswoman}}\n{{orphan|date=April 2019}}\n'''Bola Adesola''' is an accountant in [[Federal Republic of Nigeria|Nigeria]]. She is the Senior Vice-Chairman at Standard Chartered Bank Group where she was previously the CEO of Standard Chartered Bank for Nigeria and West Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/standard-chartered-appoints-bola-adesola-as-senior-vice-chairman-africa/|title=Standard Chartered appoints Bola Adesola as Senior Vice Chairman, Africa|date=11 January 2019|publisher=|access-date=8 March 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190329074435/https://www.vanguardngr.com/2019/01/standard-chartered-appoints-bola-adesola-as-senior-vice-chairman-africa/|archive-date=29 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref